<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ken Starr May Have Final Word </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Offstage while the Senate deals with the final  
act in the impeachment of President Clinton, the man who wrote the 
script for it has not rested his cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth Starr has only lowered his profile since the House  
approved the perjury and cover-up charges he framed and sent them 
to the Senate for trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The special prosecutor may yet have a role in the outcome,  
should there be a Senate attempt to punish the president without 
firing him. That could involve Starr because a censure settlement 
involving admissions would leave Clinton vulnerable to the 
independent counsel's prosecutors after his term ends. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's Office of Independent Counsel still has targets to  
pursue, with indictments and at trial. His spokesman said they may 
be operating for another two years or more, before wrapping up what 
began as their Whitewater investigation with a final report. 
</P>
<P>
	That would be longer than any special prosecutor in the 20 years  
of the independent counsel law, which expires in June. Even if the 
law lapses, Starr would be entitled to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	And after noon on Jan. 20, 2001, there would be no bar to the  
indictment of a censured former president. Starr said so when he 
testified before the House Judiciary Committee. He didn't say he 
would seek to do it. He has not said he wouldn't. Friends now say 
he has not ruled out a settlement in which Clinton would be spared 
future prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	In an extraordinary year of presidential sex scandal and lies  
about it -- Clinton won't admit lying, let alone the perjury charged 
in the impeachment -- Starr wielded powers without precedent. He 
went beyond the specific letter of the independent counsel law in 
recommending impeachment on 11 counts, among them the grand jury 
perjury and obstruction of justice charges on which the House 
impeached the president on Dec. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second impeachment of a president; charges were  
brought against Richard M. Nixon but he resigned before the House 
acted. And it was the first in which the House did not initiate the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr did, under a provision of the law stating the independent  
counsels ``shall advise the House of Representatives of any 
substantial and credible information ... that may constitute 
grounds for an impeachment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He delivered the information, 36 boxes of grand jury and other  
evidence, and more -- plus a 453-page report of his case against 
Clinton and 11 impeachment charges he recommended. 
</P>
<P>
	``I recognize that the House of Representatives -- not an  
independent counsel -- has the sole power to impeach,'' Starr began 
when he testified before the House Judiciary Committee on Nov. 18. 
But under the independent counsel act, Starr had the power to begin 
it. When Congress considered impeaching Nixon, it acted on its own. 
The Watergate special prosecutor wouldn't share his grand jury 
evidence with the House Judiciary Committee, saying he was bound by 
the rules of secrecy. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr decided that he was not, and got court clearance to  
deliver grand jury testimony to the House, which then made it 
public. 
</P>
<P>
	The impeachment evidence was Starr's evidence, on the Monica  
Lewinsky affair and coverup that he got added to his 
Whitewater-plus investigations last Jan. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	On this Jan. 11, the Senate is due to begin its impeachment  
trial of the president, and may proceed on the same evidence, 
although House impeachment managers -- now the prosecutors -- want to 
summon witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Either way, no single figure in all of this has been more  
powerful than Starr, appointed by a panel of three federal judges 
nearly 4 1/2 years ago, to take over the Whitewater investigation, 
with alleged abuses in White House travel office firings and 
mishandling of FBI files, with the Lewinsky affair added to his 
franchise later. 
</P>
<P>
	Should it come to censure, ``the only option left'' for lack of  
the 67 votes it would take to convict Clinton, according to GOP 
Sen. Orrin Hatch, Starr could be central once again. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans and some Democrats talking of censure -- others are  
adamant against a fallback penalty -- have insisted that Clinton 
admit to lying under oath as part of any censure settlement. Even 
were he to waver in his denials, his lawyers could be expected to 
balk at admissions that could be used against him for prosecution 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Were Starr to rule out prosecution for a confession as part of a  
censure settlement, one obstacle would be removed. But it could 
raise another one -- there have been suggestions in Congress that 
censure would suffice only because Clinton could ultimately face 
perjury prosecution, to demonstrate that no citizen is above the 
law. 
</P>
<P>
	That's hypothetical. Starr didn't answer questions about his  
plans even when his terse driveway interviews and that smile as he 
drove away to the office were regular TV fare. 
</P>
<P>
	None of that now. He's silent, but not nearly finished.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
