<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden's Wiberg Wins Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARIBOR, Slovenia (AP) -- Sweden's Pernilla Wiberg made a  
stunning comeback Sunday to win the women's World Cup slalom -- her 
first victory of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninth after the first run, Wiberg powered down the foggy and  
chopped-up course 57.55 seconds -- the fastest second run, though 
.22 seconds slower than her first. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think I could win because the time difference after  
the first run was too big,'' Wiberg said. ``I just thought I would 
be happy finishing in the top five.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time Olympic winner finished with a combined time of 1  
minute, 54.88 seconds to post her 23rd World Cup victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Hilde Gerg, fresh off a super-G victory here Saturday,  
finished second, just .29 seconds off Wiberg's pace. Another Swede, 
Ylva Nowen, placed third at 1:55.37. 
</P>
<P>
	American Kristina Koznick, in second after the opening run, had  
trouble handling the holes that developed along the course in the 
second run and slid to ninth place. 
</P>
<P>
	``The course didn't hold up very well,'' said a disappointed  
Koznick, who cried on her trainer's shoulder at the finish-line. 
``Even though I knew there were going to be many ruts, I just made 
too many mistakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A week ago, Koznick scored her first victory of the season in a  
night slalom in Semmering, Austria. She said her confidence was not 
shaken, however, for the upcoming World Championships in Vail, 
Colorado in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiberg, who hadn't won a race in two years, proved she is still  
a force to contend with on the women's tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``My skiing has been getting better and better each race,''  
Wiberg said. ``Now my goal is to win the Worlds in Vail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to her three Olympic and five World Championship  
medals, Wiberg also captured the overall World Cup title in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	She also won the slalom in Maribor in 1997.  
</P>
<P>
	Gerg and Martina Ertl put in a great showing for Germany over  
the two days of racing in Maribor, finishing 1-2 in the super-G on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Germans always ski well in Maribor and this year it was  
the same,'' Gerg said. ``I think it was a very good beginning to 
the new year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
