<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bills' Owner Mum on Officiating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- This time, Ralph Wilson kept quiet.  
</P>
<P>
	The Bills owner was given a chance to vent in the wake of  
another frustrating loss in which his team pointed fingers at the 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, who joined in the chorus for instant replay, was fined  
$50,000 by the league for criticizing officials after dubious calls 
contributed to a critical loss in New England in November. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Wilson apparently chose to keep both his mouth and  
his checkbook closed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills had an apparent touchdown taken away in a 24-17  
wild-card loss to Miami on Saturday, and some players were still 
fuming a day later as they cleaned out their lockers. But Wilson, 
through a spokesman, declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills, set back 93 yards by nine penalties in the loss, were  
most critical of the officials' spotting of the ball just inside 
the Miami 1-yard line after an apparent touchdown catch by Andre 
Reed with under two minutes left. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Bills criticized some of the flags, they waited for  
others that never fell. They claimed two of their players were held 
after Eric Moulds caught a long pass on the Bills' first play and 
fumbled. Moulds and Reed both appeared to be held by Miami 
defensive backs as they struggled to get to the loose ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed said the officiating in the league this season was the  
worst he's seen ``in 20 years.'' And he was not alone in that 
assessment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills were still simmering from the Nov. 29 loss at New  
England. After Shawn Jefferson was given a sideline catch on which 
replays showed he didn't get either foot in-bounds, a pass 
interference call on a desperation heave by Drew Bledsoe gave New 
England one more play. Ben Coates' TD won the game for the 
Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson took his anger out on the officials. Then he took his  
lumps. The 80-year-old owner said he wished he could call the stock 
market as well as he could predict incompetence on the part of the 
NFL officials. Teams are prohibited from criticizing the officials 
and he was fined $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, who has voted against replay in the past but now is  
championing its return, ripped Paul Tagliabue after the 
commissioner said Wilson would be fined for complaining. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't need pompous lectures from the commissioner and I feel  
that the $50,000 is not only unwarranted, but punitive in nature. 
The next time he may ask me to sit in the corner,'' Wilson said at 
the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson came away with a game ball when the players showed their  
appreciation for his outspokenness after their 33-20 win in 
Cincinnati, one week after the loss to the Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Smith shook his head as he cleaned out his locker on  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what the answer is,'' he said. ``There were  
definitely some things that were called yesterday that shouldn't 
have been called. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then again, we did some things that put ourselves in a bad  
situation, as well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
