<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pats' Coach Confident He'll Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Sports Writer-    	
</P>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The comparisons have been constant  
since Pete Carroll succeeded Bill Parcells as coach of the 
Patriots. And Carroll has always finished second. 
</P>
<P>
	So it didn't matter to detractors that he led New England to two  
playoff berths in his two seasons, overcoming numerous injuries to 
do that. Reports surfaced that a bad performance Sunday against 
Jacksonville could put his job in serious jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll, who has three years left on his contract, didn't agree.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm coming back to put together a football team that can win  
the championship,'' he said after Sunday's 25-10 playoff loss to 
the Jaguars. ``With good health and good fortune, we'll do the 
things that we dream about doing and things that we set as our 
goals. And I'm going to be part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The player-friendly Carroll stepped into a difficult situation.  
Parcells, one of the NFL's top coaches, had just led the Patriots 
to the Super Bowl, then jumped to the New York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Patriots were 10-6 in Carroll's first season and only a  
one-point loss to Pittsburgh kept them from the AFC title game. 
They were 9-7 this season despite injuries to many key players, 
including Drew Bledsoe, Terry Glenn, Ted Johnson and Todd Collins, 
who all missed Sunday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet a few days after five other NFL coaches were fired, a member  
of the Patriots' front office reportedly planted a newspaper item 
last week that Carroll might be in trouble, according to a 
published report. 
</P>
<P>
	Linebacker Chris Slade said the Patriots were outplayed and  
outcoached in a 31-10 loss to Parcells and the New York Jets in the 
regular-season finale. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, though, Slade said, ``As far as I'm concerned, Pete  
Carroll's the head coach of the Patriots and that's the way it's 
going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some veterans have spoken fondly of Parcells, a more assertive  
coach, but after the loss no Patriots criticized Carroll. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's fair'' to blame him, strong safety Lawyer  
Milloy said. ``All he does is prepare us to go out and play. He 
didn't think at the beginning of the year he was going to lose so 
many starters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All-Pro cornerback Ty Law, beaten by Jimmy Smith for a 37-yard  
scoring pass that put the Jaguars ahead 19-10 early in the fourth 
quarter, said coaching changes don't have to be disruptive. He 
cited the switch to Carroll as an example. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like Pete Carroll. I like Bill Parcells,'' Law said. ``We're  
getting to know him (Carroll). He's getting to know us a lot 
better. He's `The Man' on the team right now, so I have no doubt 
that he'll be back. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pete has 100 percent Ty Law's backing, if it means anything.''  
</P>
<P>
	``There's been a lot of talk about Pete, but Pete can't get out  
and play for us,'' wide receiver Shawn Jefferson said. ``Good game 
plans ... are put in place. It's up to these guys to execute the 
game plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, the only opinion that counts belongs to Patriots  
owner Robert Kraft, who had high praise for Carroll when the coach 
was hired. And Kraft has been silent publicly. 
</P>
<P>
	But Carroll said they've gotten along well,  
</P>
<P>
	``We've been together on everything we've done,'' Carroll said.  
``He has been terrific about it. ... Everything has been very 
amicable.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
