<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Landmark Years in Chicago's History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Major events in the history of Chicago:  
</P>
<P>
	1779 -- Jean Baptiste Point du Sable, a fur trader of  
French-African descent, builds the first settlement at the mouth of 
the Chicago River. Today all agree that the name Chicago comes from 
an Indian word. Some say it means ``strong and great.'' Others say 
it means ``wild onion'' or ``skunk.'' 

</P>
<P>
	1830 -- Lots are sold to finance construction of what would  
become the Illinois and Michigan Canal, connecting Chicago with the 
Mississippi River. 

</P>
<P>
	1833 -- Chicago incorporated as a town; population 350.  

</P>
<P>
	1834 -- A settler kills the last bear seen downtown, on what will  
become State Street. 

</P>
<P>
	1837 -- Chicago incorporated as a city; population 4,170.  

</P>
<P>
	1848 -- Illinois and Michigan Canal completed; first locomotive  
arrives from the Galena &AMP; Chicago Union Railroad. 

</P>
<P>
	1859 -- Retail baron Potter Palmer buys a mile of State Street,  
builds Palmer House hotel. 

</P>
<P>
	1865 --Opwning of Chicago Union Stock Yards.  

</P>
<P>
	1871 -- The Great Chicago Fire kills 300 people, leaves 90,000  
homeless. 

</P>
<P>
	1872 -- World's first mail-order business, Montgomery Ward,  
founded. 

</P>
<P>
	1893 -- Chicago hosts the World's Columbian Exposition,  
attracting nearly 26 million visitors during its six-month run; 
city gets first elevated trains. 

</P>
<P>
	1900 -- After epidemics of disease, engineers reverse flow of  
Chicago River so waste will not flow into Lake Michigan. 

</P>
<P>
	1907 -- University of Chicago physicist Albert Michelson becomes  
first American to win Nobel Prize for science. 

</P>
<P>
	1909 -- Newly formed Chicago Plan Commission publishes Daniel  
Burnham's comprehensive plan, which includes unobstructed 
lakefront, citywide system of parks and green belt of forest 
preserves. 

</P>
<P>
	1915 -- Lake passenger steamer Eastland sinks in the Chicago  
River; 844 drown. 

</P>
<P>
	1922 -- Fred Fisher writes the song ``Chicago,'' immortalizing  
State Street as ``that great street,'' where ``they do things they 
don't do on Broadway.'' 

</P>
<P>
	1925 -- Al Capone becomes head of Chicago underworld.  

</P>
<P>
	1929 -- Seven members of ``Bugs'' Moran's gang killed in the St.  
Valentine's Day Massacre. 

</P>
<P>
	1931 -- Capone convicted of tax evasion; sentenced to 11 years in  
prison. 

</P>
<P>
	1933 -- A Century of Progress World's Fair draws 39 million  
visitors. 

</P>
<P>
	1942 -- University of Chicago becomes the site of the world's  
first controlled atomic reaction. 

</P>
<P>
	1955 -- Richard J. Daley elected mayor.  

</P>
<P>
	1968 -- Police clash with protesters against Vietnam War at  
Democratic National Convention. 

</P>
<P>
	1971 -- Closure of Chicago Union Stock Yards.  

</P>
<P>
	1974 -- Sears Tower opens. At 1,454 feet it is the world's  
tallest building. 

</P>
<P>
	1976 -- Richard J. Daley dies during sixth term.  

</P>
<P>
	1983 -- Harold Washington is elected the city's first black  
mayor. 

</P>
<P>
	1989 -- Washington dies midway through second term.  

</P>
<P>
	1989 -- Richard M. Daley elected to fill out Washington's term.  

</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sources: Chicago Mosaic, Chicago Public Library, Chicago  
Historical Society 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
