<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Time Gets Osama bin Laden Admission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Exiled Saudi billionaire Osama bin Laden appears  
to admit in a Time magazine interview that he instigated the 
terrorist bombing of two U.S. embassies in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	The interview seems to be the closest that bin Laden has come to  
admitting a role in the deadly attacks. He has previously denied 
any role. 
</P>
<P>
	Time said the interview was conducted Dec. 22 at bin Laden's  
secret encampment in Afghanistan. He was specifically asked if he 
was responsible for the embassy attacks, and he couched his 
response in religious references -- like he did with most questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the instigation for jihad (holy war) against the Jews and  
the Americans... is considered a crime, then let history be a 
witness that I am a criminal,'' bin Laden said in the Jan. 11 issue 
of Time magazine. ``Our job is to instigate, and by the grace of 
God, we did that, and certain people responded to this 
instigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Dec. 24, a Pakistani news agency had quoted bin Laden as  
saying he was ``not involved'' in the bombing ``but I don't regret 
what happened there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials have indicted bin Laden on charges of  
masterminding terrorist bomb attacks on American embassies in Kenya 
and Tanzania Aug. 7 that killed 224 people, including 12 Americans. 
He also is suspected in terrorist attacks on U.S. targets in Saudi 
Arabia and other incidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States retaliated 13 days later with cruise missile  
raids on bin Laden's mountain hideout in northern Afghanistan, and 
a plant in Khartoum, Sudan, that was suspected of making nerve gas 
components for bin Laden. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he knew two men in custody in the United States in  
connection with the bombings, bin Laden replied: ``What I do know 
is that those who risked their lives to earn the pleasure of God 
are real men. They managed to rid the Islamic nation of disgrace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bin Laden said he knew one of the two, Wadi el-Hage, but had not  
seen or heard from him in several years. He said el-Hage ``has 
nothing to do with the U.S. allegations,'' and implied that the 
second man, Mohamad Rashed-Al'Owhali, also is innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohamed Sadeek Odeh and Al-'Owhali are charged with more than  
200 counts of murder. El Hage is accused of lying about his 
relationship with bin Laden's organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 23:13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Social Security Idea Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Using stock market investments to boost the  
supply of money for Social Security is a complex and controversial 
idea that will not easily become a reality, even though President 
Clinton gave lawmakers the go-ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't as simple a question as it appears at first  
blush,'' said Rep. Clay Shaw, R-Fla., chairman of a House 
subcommittee overseeing Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Republicans long have favored plans that would try to  
fatten the retirement program by investing its money on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting with lawmakers on Dec. 9, Clinton endorsed private  
investment, in general, as one way to help prevent a cash shortfall 
expected after more than 75 million baby boomers retire and begin 
collecting benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri and the  
American Association of Retired Persons -- the nation's largest 
organization of older adults -- also are offering conditional 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason is simple: Using the stock market to try for higher  
investment returns is more appealing than the alternatives -- deep 
retirement benefit cuts or sharp tax increases. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all counting on these better returns,'' said AARP  
lobbying chief John Rother. 
</P>
<P>
	But the consensus ends there.  
</P>
<P>
	Disagreements still to be resolved include even the most basic  
question: Who would do the investing -- individual Americans in 
personal accounts or the government by investing people's Social 
Security contributions in bulk? 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has taken no position on this, although some top  
advisers, including Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, have voiced 
worries about both choices. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Republican lawmakers -- along with Federal Reserve Chairman  
Alan Greenspan -- are against bulk investments that would mean 
government ownership of corporate stock. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want the federal government running America's  
corporations, that's socialism, and we sure don't want politics 
getting involved in the investments,'' Shaw said. 
</P>
<P>
	A powerful lobbying coalition of business and conservative  
groups, from the National Association of Manufacturers to the 
Center for New Black Leadership, also is opposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats argue it would be possible to set up a board of  
trustees to insulate Social Security's investment decisions from 
politics. 
</P>
<P>
	The alternative -- a new system of individual retirement savings  
accounts -- long has been favored by many Republicans and more 
recently won support from some key Democrats. Some government 
benefits likely still would be guaranteed as a safety net, and 
supporters say the power of Wall Street would leave most people 
better off. 
</P>
<P>
	But the shift would be tricky. The first problem is where money  
for the accounts would come from initially -- not to mention how 
much it would cost just to set up and maintain accounts for 148 
million American workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Many supporters suggest filling the accounts by diverting some  
of the Social Security taxes that workers now pay. But all those 
taxes -- and more -- will be needed in coming decades to pay benefits 
promised to aging baby boomers. Also, baby boomers do not have 
enough working years left to get much out of new private accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Most ideas to generate money to cover transition costs,  
including raising the retirement age or a tax increase for the 
wealthy, already are drawing fire. 
</P>
<P>
	For that reason, consensus is growing for using budget  
surpluses, administration officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the surplus and the possibility of higher returns, we  
increase the chance of having a Social Security reform package that 
keeps a strong standard of living for America's senior citizens and 
could be politically palatable enough to pass,'' said Clinton's top 
economic adviser, Gene Sperling. 
</P>
<P>
	But no one can predict how much money the nation will have to  
spare in coming years, and already there is a clamor to spend any 
surpluses for other purposes -- from tax cuts to education or 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to talk about how much of the surplus  
could be used for Social Security without starving other 
priorities,'' said Roger Hickey of the Institute for America's 
Future, coordinating a grass-roots campaign against private 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	That opposition includes the AFL-CIO and civil rights groups  
such as the NAACP. They argue the accounts would leave individuals 
-- especially low-wage workers -- at the mercy of the stock market . 
</P>
<P>
	Rother said the AARP would be willing to support personal  
accounts only if the current system's retirement income guarantees 
also are maintained somehow. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers and prominent economists are working on a variety of  
ideas to resolve such concerns. Democrats and Republicans have 
agreed to write a summary of the options that could be used as the 
basis for future negotiations. Many are cautiously optimistic that 
compromise can be reached despite the complexities. 
</P>
<P>
	Making changes to Social Security, sending checks to 44 million  
Americans as the nation's biggest benefit program, always has been 
politically perilous, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we move too quickly or these things aren't fully fleshed  
out, that could create a huge backlash,'' said Rep. Bob Matsui, 
D-Calif., a member of Shaw's subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Alice Ann Love reports on Social Security for The  
Associated Press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
