<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  DaimlerChrysler Unveils Concept Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Before the internal combustion engine dies and  
pollution-free, fuel-cell powertrains have a chance to replace it, 
motorists likely will see technologies that blend the old with the 
new. 
</P>
<P>
	They include electric-gasoline hybrids, synthetic diesel fuels  
and natural gas-powered engines. 
</P>
<P>
	That is the theory behind much of the research at  
DaimlerChrysler AG, which unveiled a trio of concept cars and 
trucks Sunday that represent the German-American automaker's 
efforts to find near-term alternatives to conventional gasoline 
power. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't bet the farm on any single technology,'' Thomas T.  
Stallkamp, president of DaimlerChrysler's North American arm, said 
at the media preview of the Detroit auto show. ``We're pretty 
excited about fuel cells in the long term.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the short term, DaimlerChrysler is betting that high-tech  
diesel fuels will meet tougher emissions standards in the next 
several years. 
</P>
<P>
	That bet is demonstrated in the Dodge Power Wagon, an oversized  
pickup packed with a 7.2-liter, turbocharged diesel engine designed 
to run on a synthetic diesel-type fuel derived from natural gas. 
Because the fuel is made from natural gas, it lacks the polluting 
sulfur that comes from crude oil-derived fuels. 
</P>
<P>
	The engine generates 250 horsepower and incredible pulling power  
while using 40 percent less fuel than a comparable gasoline 
powerplant. Which leads to another point DaimlerChrysler wants to 
make with its latest concepts: High performance and cleaner 
technology can go hand-in-hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really kind of a monster,'' said Steve Brueckner,  
DaimlerChrysler's senior manager of advanced diesel engine 
technology. ``But you can drive this and still feel good about 
yourself in the morning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker hopes the hulking truck will draw enough attention  
to refocus the debate on diesel technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Diesels emit about half as much carbon dioxide as gasoline  
engines. Carbon dioxide is a so-called greenhouse gas that is 
believed to be contributing to global warming. But conventional 
diesels also release more soot and oxides of nitrogen. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists have been lobbying against diesels, even as a  
near-term solution. California regulators recently adopted tougher 
vehicle emissions rules that did away with special exemptions for 
diesel engines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Union of Concerned Scientists argues that the refining  
process for the Power Wagon's new fuel generates twice the 
greenhouse gases of refining conventional diesel, which reduces the 
engine's pollution savings. 
</P>
<P>
	Stallkamp said such problems can be resolved through continued  
research, however. Of all the technologies DaimlerChrysler is 
studying, the diesel hybrid is the closest to being practical for 
everyday use, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler also unveiled two other concept cars Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	The Chrysler Citadel, a sport sedan with a hybrid powertrain,  
uses a V6 engine to drive the rear wheels and an electric motor to 
drive the front wheels. DaimlerChrysler officials say the result is 
the equivalent power of a V8, lower emissions and V6 fuel economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodge Charger R/T uses a supercharged, 325-horsepower V8  
engine powered by compressed natural gas and is designed to be a 
clean-burning muscle car. Its key technology is a new storage tank 
that takes up less space than a typical, heavy tank needed for 
compressed natural gas. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem with natural gas is there is no widespread system of  
filling stations. For now, the best hope for natural gas vehicles 
is with business and government fleets. 
</P>
<P>
	At last week's Los Angeles Auto Show, DaimlerChrysler also  
unveiled an experimental fuel-cell-powered sport utility vehicle 
called the Jeep Commander. It is designed to use methanol as its 
main energy source, which would be converted on board to the 
hydrogen a fuel cell needs to create electricity. At present, 
however, the system does not work. 
</P>
<P>
	``Long term, that's the right way,'' Stallkamp said. ``It's the  
cleanest and most efficient.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
