<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Snow, Ice Shut Down Midwest Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The year's first major winter storm pummeled the eastern half of  
the country Saturday with more than a foot of snow in the upper 
Midwest and freezing rain as far south as the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines canceled hundreds of flights to and from major Midwest  
hubs, frustrating travelers trying to get home after the holidays. 
The storm was expected to spread its icy, dangerous driving 
conditions to the Northeast on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	By Saturday night, the storm had dumped 17 inches at Chicago's  
Midway Airport, 12 inches in Milwaukee and 11 inches on Detroit 
Metropolitan Airport. More than 50 of Indiana's counties and cities 
declared snow emergencies, banning unnecessary travel. 
</P>
<P>
	At least a dozen deaths throughout the region were blamed on the  
storm, which packed gusts of 55 mph and blew drifts up to 8 feet 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	The Postal Service even quit delivering mail in the Indianapolis  
area. Rain, slush and freezing temperatures made it too dangerous 
for carriers to walk their routes, said Postmaster Mike Lamborne. 
</P>
<P>
	At Chicago's O'Hare International Airport, American Airlines  
canceled all flights through midnight Saturday and United shut down 
everything after midafternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	United spokesman Matt Triaca said anyone planning to fly out of  
O'Hare should wait until Monday or Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	TWA canceled nearly 400 morning flights at its main hub in St.  
Louis. The shutdown triggered delays and other cancellations across 
the country, including Denver and New York City's three major 
airports. Northwest Airlines shut down about 150 flights systemwide 
and Delta canceled dozens of flights to the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Near-blizzard conditions in the north and glazed roadways  
farther south sent drivers spinning off roads from Wisconsin to New 
Jersey to South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could hardly see driving to work. I prayed all the way to  
work,'' Belinda Bates, a hostess at a Detroit restaurant, said 
Saturday. ``You can't hardly see cause the snow is coming down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Wisconsin, more than 110 vehicles were involved in two  
massive pileups on Interstate 94, and at least one person died in 
the accidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The southern flank of the storm carried tornadoes and severe  
thunderstorms into Florida. More than a dozen homes and cars were 
destroyed by tornadoes and high winds in the northern part of the 
state, while more than 100 homes to the south in Palm Beach County 
were flooded by heavy rains. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
