<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 13:59:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan PM Escapes Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- A powerful bomb shattered a bridge and  
killed four people Sunday shortly before Pakistan's prime minister 
was to cross it. Police said a delay at home saved the leader and 
his family from the assassination attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said the bombing, which also left three people  
wounded and two missing in rubble, was carried out by an ethnic 
party formerly allied with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. 
</P>
<P>
	The roar of the 4:50 a.m. explosion could be heard for miles  
around Raiwind, the site of Sharif's private residence, 13 miles 
from Lahore. Police said the bomb exploded when he normally crosses 
the bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharif's wife, Kusloom, said she just couldn't get her family  
moving this particular morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a delay in our preparation and we were at home when  
the blast occurred,'' she told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Information Minister Mushahid Hussain said Sharif was unshaken  
by the explosion: ``He is more concerned about those who died and 
were wounded in the explosion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three civilians and a police officer died. Police say they fear  
another two people still may be buried in the rubble. Three 
policemen were wounded, according to doctors and police officers in 
Lahore said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are investigating all the aspects of the case,'' Hussain  
said, ``but it is too early to blame someone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police, however, suspect the ethnic Muttahida Qami Movement. A  
police source speaking on condition of anonymity said three MQM 
workers have been arrested in the southern city of Karachi in 
connection with the blast. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also raided MQM offices in Lahore, but made no arrests.  
</P>
<P>
	MQM leaders say blaming their group is another attempt by  
Sharif's government to destroy their political base in southern 
Sindh province and force their leaders underground. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government wants to use this incident to launch a fresh  
crackdown on our party,'' said Farooq Sattar, an MQM spokesman at a 
news conference in Karachi. ``They want to eliminate the MQM.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharif blames the MQM for most of the violence in Karachi, the  
capital of southern Sindh province and Pakistan's largest city of 
14 million, which has been controlled by the MQM since the 
mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,000 people died in political and religious violence  
there last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The MQM, which represents Urdu-speaking people who immigrated  
from British India at independence in 1947, denies the accusations 
and says the government is engaging in ``state-sponsored 
terrorism'' against its ethnic group. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharif split with MQM in October and pledged to end the violence  
in Karachi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
