<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smithsonian Takes Show on the Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In its Washington home, the Smithsonian  
Institution reflects all stone and brick and permanence. But on the 
road it turns into a pretty spry outfit. 
</P>
<P>
	Fine art traveled from junction to junction by rail in one  
mobile Smithsonian show, the train becoming the art gallery. 
Highbrow glass creations sparkled at the Silver Dollar City 
amusement park in Branson, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	The flash of Broadway, the forlorn prairie schoolhouse, the  
murky mysteries of the Florida manatee all are being celebrated in 
shows moving from the National Mall to a shopping mall near you. 
</P>
<P>
	Or to a library, school, museum, theater or historical society --  
wherever the like-minded congregate, a touch of the human 
experience, on wheels. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been trying more and more to branch out and reach people  
where they truly live,'' said Anna Cohn, director of the 
Smithsonian Institution Traveling Exhibition Service. ``Our focus 
is on reaching the largest number of people in the widest variety 
of places.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those places range from Miami to Menomonie, Wis., both planning  
to play host to ``Red, Hot &AMP; Blue,'' a tribute to Broadway and 
Hollywood musicals. No fewer than three exhibitions about quilts 
and the people who make them have been on tour this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The traveling exhibits vary in size as much as the venues do.  
</P>
<P>
	``Barn Again: Celebrating an American Icon,'' comprises several  
dozen panels of photographs of farm buildings, along with some 
objects, that a site can exhibit for under $500. Still in 
preparation is an extravaganza marking discoveries of the Hubble 
telescope, scheduled to open in May at a cost to exhibitors of 
$100,000 for each eight-week stint. 
</P>
<P>
	For ``Red, Hot &AMP; Blue,'' opening this month, the Smithsonian is  
teaming with Turner Classic Movies and the League of Historic 
American Theaters to take an exhibit showcasing the history of 
classic musicals on tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Shorn of the theater and film artifacts that helped make the  
exhibit a hit in Washington, the much smaller touring version 
features kiosks highlighting the stars, composers and other 
creative forces behind musicals, as well as a video drawn from 
Turner's extensive archives. 
</P>
<P>
	The Smithsonian has been taking exhibits out of Washington since  
1952, but venues traditionally were large urban museums and foreign 
embassies until the 1976 bicentennial. That's when the institution 
began fanning out far and wide and into smaller places. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Ms. Cohn said, ``We have an unrivaled presence in rural  
America,'' as well as a reach into the traditional large sites. 
</P>
<P>
	As well as adapting some of the institution's popular Washington  
exhibits for the road, the traveling service creates some 
independently. Working with Woody Guthrie's family and Smithsonian 
recordings, it is putting together a show on the Depression-era 
folk singer that will contain his song manuscripts, illustrations, 
home movies and more. 
</P>
<P>
	Further ahead, 40 artists, architects and designers are creating  
time capsules marking the century's achievements and values. 
</P>
<P>
	``Millennium Messages'' will begin touring early in 2000. When  
it's done, the capsules will somehow, somewhere, disappear from 
view for a very long time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Smithsonian notes the first known time capsule, buried on  
the site of the 1939 World's Fair, was made to last 5,000 years and 
contains a slide rule, a women's hat and messages from the likes of 
Albert Einstein. 
</P>
<P>
	What might the new capsules hold to represent  
turn-of-the-century civilization? A computer mouse? The Smithsonian 
itself seems to have one foot in each century, rolling out the 
trucks and trains like a traveling circus of old while tackling a 
topic here and there solely online, such as ``Rotten Truth (About 
Garbage).'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the Internet has been more of a boon than a crowd-buster  
for museums, a way to drum up interest without persuading people to 
stay home, skip the show and see it on a computer screen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wonder often, in the next generation, or in the next two  
generations, what the impact might be,'' Ms. Cohn said. But for 
now, she said, people seem to value the direct encounter between 
viewer and object, ``a contemplative antidote to the ferocious 
speed of the electronic age.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 10:52:58 </DATE_TIME>
