<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Jan. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Backs Long-Term Care Credit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is proposing an  
unprecedented $1,000 tax credit, at a cost of billions, to 
compensate 2 million American families struggling to provide 
long-term care for elderly or disabled relatives. The tax credit, 
meant to compensate caregivers for a wide range of activities that 
tending to others requires, is part of a five-year, $6.2 billion 
package that the president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton 
will announce tomorrow. None of it becomes reality without 
Congress, which last year rejected the president's ``Patients Bill 
of Rights.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Senators Say Clinton Will Survive  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Clinton is unlikely to be removed from  
office, but his presidency is permanently blighted by his 
impeachment on charges he lied about his affair with Monica 
Lewinsky, senators said today. Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and Sen. 
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., have floated a plan under which the 
Senate, after several days of hearing arguments in the case, would 
vote on whether the charges are enough to remove the president from 
office. With a two-thirds majority unlikely, the Senate could move 
to end the trial and consider a censure motion against the 
president. 

</P>
<P>
	Midwest Storm Spreads to Northeast  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At least a dozen deaths are being blamed on the  
storm which pummeled the upper Midwest with more than a foot of 
snow and is spreading its dangerous driving conditions to the 
Northeast today. Airlines canceled hundreds of flights to and from 
major Midwest hubs. United Airlines spokesman Matt Triaca said 
anyone planning to fly out of O'Hare in Chicago should wait until 
tomorrow or Tuesday. The southern flank of the storm carried 
tornadoes and severe thunderstorms into Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	Euro Trading Begins in Australia  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- International trading began today for the euro, the  
new common currency that is expected to increase Europe's power in 
the global economy and eventually rival the U.S. dollar as the type 
of money chosen by traders and reserves. The day's first dealings 
in the euro are expected to be cautious and subdued, and that was 
clear in Sydney, Australia, where trading began at 5 a.m. Monday (1 
p.m. EST Sunday). Taxi drivers enjoyed a booming business, thanks 
to the early rising executives and traders. The 11 European nations 
that launched the euro Friday represent 20 percent of world 
economic output and 18 percent of world trade. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Detains Denver Cult Members  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli police detained eight adults and six  
children belonging to a Denver-based apocalyptic Christian cult 
today, and accused the group of planning violent acts in Jerusalem. 
Police said the group planned to provoke a bloody shoot-out by 
opening fire on Israeli police and members of the group believed 
that this catastrophic act would hasten the Second Coming. ``They 
planned to carry out violent and extreme acts in the streets of 
Jerusalem at the end of 1999 to start the process of bringing Jesus 
back to life,'' said Brig. Gen. Elihu Ben-Onn, the national police 
spokesman. 

</P>
<P>
	Saddam Challenges No-Fly Zones  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein said today  
that the no-fly zones imposed on his country by the United States 
and Britain have no basis in international law and are a ``stark 
violation'' of U.N. resolutions. Saddam, in a speech to a Cabinet 
meeting carried by the official Iraqi News Agency, also sought to 
cast doubt on American claims that its planes were firing back when 
they aimed missiles at Iraqi air defenses in two recent clashes. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan PM Escapes Assassination  
</P>
<P>
	LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- A powerful bomb shattered a bridge and  
killed four people today shortly before Pakistan's prime minister 
was to cross it, with police saying a delay at home saved the 
leader from the assassination attempt. The government said the 
bombing was carried out by an ethnic party formerly allied with 
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. A police source said three workers 
from the Muttahida Qami Movement have been arrested in the southern 
city of Karachi. MQM leaders say blaming their group is an attempt 
to destroy their political base and force their leaders 
underground. 

</P>
<P>
	Biennial World Cup Soccer Proposed  
</P>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- FIFA president Sepp Blatter proposed  
the biggest change in the history of world soccer today, saying the 
World Cup should be held every two years instead of four. The 
president of soccer's world governing body told the Zurich weekly 
SonntagsBlick that the changes would increase the status of 
national teams, which he said are threatened by proposals for a new 
Super League of European clubs. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
