<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Nervous About Inauguration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL (AP) -- Political pundits laughed at former professional  
wrestler Jesse Ventura's populist quest for the Minnesota 
governorship. He got the last laugh when voters backed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Now reality is setting in.  
</P>
<P>
	Ventura will be sworn in on Monday as the state's 37th governor.  
Admittedly nervous about the job facing him, Ventura said, ``It's 
uncharted water.'' He even joked that he fears flubbing his lines 
when reciting the oath of office in the Capitol rotunda. 
</P>
<P>
	On the bright side, the 47-year-old Ventura is glad he'll  
finally start getting a paycheck again. He's been unemployed since 
leaving a radio talk show job last summer to make the gubernatorial 
run. His new salary is $120,303. 
</P>
<P>
	Staying true to his populist campaign platform, Ventura and wife  
Terry opted to skip the traditional black-tie inaugural ball in 
favor of a ``people's celebration'' bash at the Target Center Jan. 
16 with live music. 
</P>
<P>
	The inaugural will cap Ventura's Reform Party victory, which  
shocked the career politicians he beat and many others -- seemingly 
everyone but Ventura himself. He's been locked in a media spotlight 
ever since, receiving far greater attention than he ever won acting 
in films or as a pro wrestler known as ``The Body'' for his 
impressive physique. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of Ventura T-shirts, hats, cups and bumper stickers have  
boomed since the election. Airport shops have sold thousands of 
shirts emblazoned with the slogan ``My governor can beat up your 
governor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seating at the official inauguration ceremony is limited to  
about 200 members of the public, but Ventura pledged to stand and 
shake hands for two hours afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	His plans for an inaugural speech are still up in the air.  
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't even really thought about what I'm going to talk  
about Monday,'' Ventura said last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be something for Minnesotans to feel good  
about the next four years, that we're excited, that we should all 
be excited and that their state isn't crumbling apart for what they 
did.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 16:42:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds' Larkin Still Seeking Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Shortstop Barry Larkin hasn't changed his  
stance: he wants to be traded if the Cincinnati Reds continue 
rebuilding. 
</P>
<P>
	Larkin, who attended the team's annual RedsFest this weekend,  
said he won't let his disappointment get in the way of his 
performance if the Reds choose to hold onto him. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Jim Bowden reiterated over the weekend that  
there's little chance Larkin will be dealt. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we're playing, my focus is going to be on winning,''  
Larkin said. ``This never stemmed from the players on the team. 
This stems from up top and what was going to happen and things 
changed course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old Larkin asked to be traded last season after the  
Reds began dealing their best players as part of a long-range 
rebuilding. He would like to play for a team that has a chance to 
compete for the playoffs as he approaches the end of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	After the season, agent Eric Goldschmidt reiterated the trade  
request and said Larkin would accept a trade to Los Angeles, St. 
Louis, San Diego, Texas or the Chicago Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Larkin would like to finish his career in Cincinnati, and wishes  
the Reds were more committed to winning. The Reds hope to be in 
shape to contend when they move into a new stadium, tentatively 
scheduled for 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I get a chance to go somewhere where there's an obvious  
focus to win, fine,'' Larkin said. ``Hopefully, that will be here. 
If not, I'm not going to go somewhere just to leave Cincinnati. I 
love it here. It's just a matter of wanting to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He went public with his frustrations at the front office after  
Bowden traded second baseman Bret Boone to Atlanta for a minor 
leaguer and pitcher Denny Neagle, who can demand a trade after the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past year, the Reds also have traded No. 1 starter Dave  
Burba to Cleveland for Sean Casey and closer Jeff Shaw to Los 
Angeles for Paul Konerko and Dennis Reyes. They traded Konerko to 
the Chicago White Sox after the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you try to build a foundation, you build it on something  
solid that you know about,'' Larkin said. ``Don't keep breaking 
down that foundation. That's what has been happening around here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden reiterated this weekend that he won't trade Larkin unless  
he can get some top prospects for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been offered a middle reliever and a Double-A utility  
infielder,'' Bowden said. ``There hasn't been a lot of interest in 
him. But that's OK because we'd like him to be our shortstop. We've 
said that all along.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
