<DOCNO> APW19990103.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 17:46:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  T-Bird Fanatic Placed Early Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Bill Gill has owned hundreds of T-Birds over the  
years -- he's lost track of the exact count. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, well before Ford had even hinted publicly that it  
would shelve one of its most recognized nameplates and bring it 
back on a roadster early in the next century, Gill went to his 
dealer and placed an order for two 2001 Thunderbirds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to be the first on their list,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gill was there when the concept car destined to become the 2001  
T-Bird was unveiled to the automotive press Sunday at the North 
American International Auto Show. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill, who's partial to the original 1955-57 T-Birds, said he had  
hoped the concept car would look more like the original. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice, tasteful,'' Gill said. ``I realize they had to  
change the body styling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gill suspected that a new retro T-Bird roadster was in the  
works. He owns a shop that specializes in classic T-Bird parts in 
Hazel Park outside Detroit, and Ford engineers and designers had 
been making frequent visits to buy parts and inquire whether he 
knew of any '55 and '57 'Birds for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	They put the purchases on personal credit cards, so as not to  
tip anybody off at the shop, but Gill knew they worked for Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was kind of backdoor,'' Gill recalled. ``They ended up  
buying a '55 in the Detroit area and a '57 out of Texas and started 
freshening those cars up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, the Ford employees gave up the pretense that their  
interest was purely personal. They began paying Gill with Ford 
Motor Co. checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill, who also serves as adviser to the American Road  
Thunderbird Club chapter in Dearborn, said Ford used the classic 
T-Birds to help them design the concept car that was unveiled 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the designers and engineers were just out of school and  
weren't even alive in the '50s and '60s, the T-Bird's heyday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't know what an old T-Bird was like,'' said Gill, 56.  
</P>
<P>
	There's no shortage of Ford employees who own classic T-Birds.  
Gill said Ford wisely sought out their advice in areas such as what 
the new car should look like, what colors it should use and how 
many seats it should have. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had a lot of influence in getting this thing off the  
ground,'' Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said the strong affection people have for the original  
'Bird goes beyond its unique styling: He says it's about as 
American a car as you'll find. Part of that has to do with its 
namesake, a bird with invisible wings that created the winds and 
thunder, according to Southwest Indian legend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thunderbird, American Indian, the turquoise -- there's  
turquoise in the emblems on the car,'' Gill noted. ``Our nation's 
ancestry is with the Indians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said used '55-57 T-Birds today fetch from $15,000 for one  
that's driveable and in fair condition to $200,000 for a rare '57 
with supercharged V8 engine. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 17:46:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  T-Bird Fanatic Placed Early Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Bill Gill has owned hundreds of T-Birds over the  
years -- he's lost track of the exact count. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, well before Ford had even hinted publicly that it  
would shelve one of its most recognized nameplates and bring it 
back on a roadster early in the next century, Gill went to his 
dealer and placed an order for two 2001 Thunderbirds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to be the first on their list,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gill was there when the concept car destined to become the 2001  
T-Bird was unveiled to the automotive press Sunday at the North 
American International Auto Show. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill, who's partial to the original 1955-57 T-Birds, said he had  
hoped the concept car would look more like the original. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice, tasteful,'' Gill said. ``I realize they had to  
change the body styling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gill suspected that a new retro T-Bird roadster was in the  
works. He owns a shop that specializes in classic T-Bird parts in 
Hazel Park outside Detroit, and Ford engineers and designers had 
been making frequent visits to buy parts and inquire whether he 
knew of any '55 and '57 'Birds for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	They put the purchases on personal credit cards, so as not to  
tip anybody off at the shop, but Gill knew they worked for Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was kind of backdoor,'' Gill recalled. ``They ended up  
buying a '55 in the Detroit area and a '57 out of Texas and started 
freshening those cars up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, the Ford employees gave up the pretense that their  
interest was purely personal. They began paying Gill with Ford 
Motor Co. checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill, who also serves as adviser to the American Road  
Thunderbird Club chapter in Dearborn, said Ford used the classic 
T-Birds to help them design the concept car that was unveiled 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the designers and engineers were just out of school and  
weren't even alive in the '50s and '60s, the T-Bird's heyday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't know what an old T-Bird was like,'' said Gill, 56.  
</P>
<P>
	There's no shortage of Ford employees who own classic T-Birds.  
Gill said Ford wisely sought out their advice in areas such as what 
the new car should look like, what colors it should use and how 
many seats it should have. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had a lot of influence in getting this thing off the  
ground,'' Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said the strong affection people have for the original  
'Bird goes beyond its unique styling: He says it's about as 
American a car as you'll find. Part of that has to do with its 
namesake, a bird with invisible wings that created the winds and 
thunder, according to Southwest Indian legend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thunderbird, American Indian, the turquoise -- there's  
turquoise in the emblems on the car,'' Gill noted. ``Our nation's 
ancestry is with the Indians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said used '55-57 T-Birds today fetch from $15,000 for one  
that's driveable and in fair condition to $200,000 for a rare '57 
with supercharged V8 engine. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 15:45:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> T-Bird Fanatic Placed Early Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Bill Gill has owned hundreds of T-Birds over the  
years -- he's lost track of the exact count. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, well before Ford had even hinted publicly that it  
would shelve one of its most recognized nameplates and bring it 
back on a roadster early in the next century, Gill went to his 
dealer and placed an order for two 2001 Thunderbirds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to be the first on their list,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gill was there when the concept car destined to become the 2001  
T-Bird was unveiled to the automotive press Sunday at the North 
American International Auto Show. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill, who's partial to the original 1955-57 T-Birds, said he had  
hoped the concept car would look more like the original. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice, tasteful,'' Gill said. ``I realize they had to  
change the body styling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gill suspected that a new retro T-Bird roadster was in the  
works. He owns a shop that specializes in classic T-Bird parts in 
Hazel Park outside Detroit, and Ford engineers and designers had 
been making frequent visits to buy parts and inquire whether he 
knew of any '55 and '57 'Birds for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	They put the purchases on personal credit cards, so as not to  
tip anybody off at the shop, but Gill knew they worked for Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was kind of backdoor,'' Gill recalled. ``They ended up  
buying a '55 in the Detroit area and a '57 out of Texas and started 
freshening those cars up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, the Ford employees gave up the pretense that their  
interest was purely personal. They began paying Gill with Ford 
Motor Co. checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill, who also serves as adviser to the American Road  
Thunderbird Club chapter in Dearborn, said Ford used the classic 
T-Birds to help them design the concept car that was unveiled 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the designers and engineers were just out of school and  
weren't even alive in the '50s and '60s, the T-Bird's heyday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't know what an old T-Bird was like,'' said Gill, 56.  
</P>
<P>
	There's no shortage of Ford employees who own classic T-Birds.  
Gill said Ford wisely sought out their advice in areas such as what 
the new car should look like, what colors it should use and how 
many seats it should have. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had a lot of influence in getting this thing off the  
ground,'' Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said the strong affection people have for the original  
'Bird goes beyond its unique styling: He says it's about as 
American a car as you'll find. Part of that has to do with its 
namesake, a bird with invisible wings that created the winds and 
thunder, according to Southwest Indian legend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thunderbird, American Indian, the turquoise -- there's  
turquoise in the emblems on the car,'' Gill noted. ``Our nation's 
ancestry is with the Indians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said used '55-57 T-Birds today fetch from $15,000 for one  
that's driveable and in fair condition to $200,000 for a rare '57 
with supercharged V8 engine. 

</P>
</TEXT>
