<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jesse Ventura Merchandise Popular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- With appearances on network news and  
late-night talk shows, CNN and C-SPAN, Jesse Ventura has peddled 
his political shtick to millions. Now, quite a few of them are 
literally buying it. 
</P>
<P>
	You'd expect the Reform Party governor to be popular in the  
state that just elected him. But his appeal has gone national, with 
people all over the country gobbling up Ventura T-shirts, hats and 
bumper stickers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen (Ventura merchandise) all over the place. You  
combine the yearning for a different political way with the 
personality of Jesse and you see what you get,'' said Dean Barkley, 
Ventura's campaign chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	David Kahn, a retiree who lives in Windsor, Calif., had his  
niece in Minneapolis ship two black Ventura T-shirts his way. He's 
keeping one for himself and giving the other to his son. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was really interesting that he won. I'm not just  
buying the T-shirts for a joke,'' said Kahn, who followed Ventura 
during his pro wrestling days. Kahn still has an original Ventura 
action figure from when his children were young. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ventura rush started the day after his surprise victory Nov.  
3. 
</P>
<P>
	Salesmen started calling Host Marriott, concessionaire at the  
Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport, early the next morning 
and they've had hundreds of calls since, said marketing manager 
Sarah Londerville. 
</P>
<P>
	Host Marriott has sold 5,000 T-shirts emblazoned with ``My  
governor can beat up your governor'' at its five airport gift shops 
in the past two months, Londerville said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the 51 Target stores in Minnesota, supplies of ``Mind Your  
Body'' T-shirts and sweatshirts, ``Man of Action'' hats and ``My 
governor can beat up your governor'' mugs have to be replenished 
every week, said Target spokeswoman Denise Workcuff. 
</P>
<P>
	Signature Group, one of the few companies licensed to sell the  
goods, has shipped products to J.C. Penney Co. and Musicland Stores 
across the country. Mervyn's also is opening a national account, 
said Peter Lambert, co-owner of the Plymouth-based retail chain. 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Friedline, Ventura's former campaign manager, said recently  
that he got 25 requests for Ventura T-shirts in a three-day span. 
Only two of them were from Minnesotans. Now he's trying to figure 
out how to reprint and sell Ventura's campaign lawn signs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in charge of marketing a governor. Who would have ever  
thought that would happen?'' Friedline said. 
</P>
<P>
	The next item that will mix politics with the free market is a  
beefy action figure in Ventura's likeness, bald head and all. 
Contrary to the wild attire of the Ventura doll from his wrestling 
days, the new one -- due out this spring -- shows the governor-elect 
in a business suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura's custom-made doll stole the show in Ventura's campaign  
commercials, which depicted two boys playing with a Ventura doll 
banging his fist on a desk and dismissing Evil Special Interest 
Man. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Hillsman, the man who produced Ventura's campaign ads, said  
they created the doll -- a combination of several action figure 
parts -- as a surrogate for the candidate who didn't have enough 
time to shoot the TV spots. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had no idea that there'd actually be people clamoring for an  
action figure. But this is America,'' Hillsman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura said he's flattered by the demand for products with his  
face or name. 
</P>
<P>
	``My job is to do everything I can for the state of Minnesota.  
If that's part of it then, yeah, I suppose it's gratifying to know 
that I'm already helping and I haven't even been sworn in yet,'' he 
said ahead of his Monday swearing-in ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	But the future first lady, Terry Ventura, said she was a bit  
frustrated by all the unlicensed paraphernalia being sold. The 
governor-elect has been out of work since he left his radio job 
last summer to run for office. 
</P>
<P>
	While Ventura profited from the sale of his first action figure  
during his pro wrestling days (he bought a Porsche with the 
proceeds), he won't see any of it this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, his campaign is amassing the proceeds from its sales  
for future campaigns. In the two months since the election, 
Ventura's campaign has sold tens of thousands of dollars in 
T-shirts and hats at $20 a clip. Other products are being 
discussed, including a Ventura educational comic book that would 
promote a healthy lifestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	A nonprofit corporation, Ventura for Minnesota Inc., has been  
formed to license the products. Profits are being held in escrow 
until the Minnesota Campaign Finance and Disclosure Board 
determines how Ventura's office can spend the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Gitlin, a professor of journalism, culture and sociology at  
New York University, said Ventura's popularity will eventually wane 
outside Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also said he can't think of another governor who has been  
able to market himself as Ventura has done. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't imagine anything competing,'' he said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 18:13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tamara Dudko    	
</P>
<P>
	MINSK, Belarus (AP) -- Tamara Dudko, the deputy speaker of  
Belarus' upper house of parliament, died Saturday in a car 
accident, state-run television announced Sunday. She was 53. 
</P>
<P>
	No other details were available.  
</P>
<P>
	Dudko, who was a member of the Supreme Soviet under the last  
Soviet leader, Mikhail Gorbachev, was an engineer by training and 
was general director of Belarus' largest brewery, Alivariya. 
</P>
<P>
	She was appointed to parliament by President Alexander  
Lukashenko in January 1997, after he pushed through a referendum 
creating a new legislature to replace the one he dissolved. 

</P>
<P>
 *Rolf Liebermann    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Swiss composer Rolf Liebermann, who led the Hamburg  
Opera for more than a decade before sparking the revival of the 
moribund Paris Opera, died Saturday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Liebermann spent 13 years as head of the Hamburg Opera, from  
1959 to 1972, before joining the Paris Opera as chief administrator 
at a time when it was being abandoned by the public and by stars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Liebermann years, from 1973-80, ``were those of revival,  
reform and a period of great splendor,'' Paris Opera Director 
Hughes Gall said in a telephone interview with The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking on the revival of the Paris Opera, Liebermann brought in  
some of the world's great conductors, including Karl Bohm, Pierre 
Boulez, Lorin Maazel and Georg Solti. He even tapped the film and 
theater worlds, bringing in directors like Joseph Losey. 

</P>
<P>
 *David Lynch    	
</P>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- David E. Lynch, a former Washington  
correspondent for several Lincoln newspapers, died Thursday after a 
long fight with cancer. He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch covered regional news from the nation's capital for  
various newspapers for more than 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch became the correspondent for the former Lincoln Journal  
and the Sunday Lincoln Journal-Star in 1982 and continued in that 
role until Lee Enterprises bought the Lincoln Journal in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Milford, Mass., he was a general assignment reporter  
for the Worcester Telegram and Gazette in Massachusetts from 1965 
to 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970 he became the Washington correspondent for the  
Griffin-Larrabee News Bureau, a regional news service covering the 
northeast part of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1974 he became an investigative reporter and acting assistant  
city editor in the home office of the Buffalo Courier-Express in 
New York. In 1977 he was assigned to the Washington bureau for the 
newspaper, which no longer exists. 
</P>
<P>
	When he left the Courier-Express he opened his own news service  
called Lynch Communications. He took on clients included the 
Lincoln Journal, the Cedar Rapids Gazette and Data Transmission 
Network. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors inlcude his wife, a daughter and two brothers.  

</P>
<P>
 *David Manners    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) -- David Manners, who played the  
romantic hero in such classic horror films as ``Dracula'' and ``The 
Mummy,'' died Dec. 23. He was 98. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he appeared in more than three dozen films, Manners was  
best known for playing the stalwart hero or the love interest in 
the horror films of the 1930s. 
</P>
<P>
	He played Jonathan Harker to Bela Lugosi's Dracula in the 1931  
film and fought to keep his lover from the clutches of Boris 
Karloff in 1932's ``The Mummy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His many non-horror roles included the fiance of Katherine  
Hepburn in her screen debut, 1932's ``A Bill of Divorcement,'' 
which co-starred John Barrymore. 
</P>
<P>
	Manngers made his stage debut in 1924 at the Hart House Theater  
in Toronto. He also performed plays in New York and Chicago before 
moving to Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	He also did stage work in the 1940s in New York.  
</P>
<P>
	He eventually left the entertainment field for a Mojave Desert  
ranch and kept a journal, excerpts of which were published as 
``Awakening from a Dream of Me.'' He also wrote several other 
books, including the novels ``Convenient Season'' and ``Under 
Running Laughter.'' 

</P>
<P>
 *Jerry Quarry    	
</P>
<P>
	TEMPLETON, Calif. (AP) -- Jerry Quarry, a popular heavyweight  
boxer who fought Muhammad Ali and Floyd Patterson then eventually 
lapsed into a punch-drunk fog, died Sunday after being taken off 
life support. He was 53. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarry was hospitalized Dec. 28 with pneumonia and then suffered  
cardiac arrest while at Twin Cities Community Hospital. He died 
after family members told doctors to remove him from life support, 
said Claude Sutherland, a longtime family friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarry, who earned $2.1 million in purses as a top contender in  
the 1960s and '70s, later lived on Social Security checks. By the 
age of 50, the pounding he had taken in the ring turned him into a 
confused, childlike man whose relatives had to take care of him. 
</P>
<P>
	He suffered from dementia pugilistica, severe brain damage  
caused by repeated blows to the head. Neurological tests revealed 
early signs of dementia in 1982, before his short-term memory loss 
and motor skills deteriorated so noticeably and before his last 
three fights. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the highlights of Quarry's career were two fights against  
Patterson, the former heavyweight champion. The first ended in a 
draw, and he won the second on a controversial split decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarry, a 6-foot, 195-pounder, earned his biggest payday of  
$338,000 by fighting Ali when Ali returned from his banishment from 
boxing in 1970. 

</P>
<P>
 *Oscar Scaggs    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Oscar Scaggs, the son of singer Boz Scaggs,  
died Thursday of a drug overdose, according to the musician's 
publicist. He was 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Additional details about his death were not released.  
</P>
<P>
	Boz Scaggs, 54, recorded two albums with the Steve Miller Band  
before embarking on a solo career in 1968. He achieved success in 
the late 1960s and 1970s with hits like ``Lowdown,'' ``Lido 
Shuffle'' and ``We're All Alone.'' 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 17:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pats' Coach Confident He'll Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Sports Writer-    	
</P>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The comparisons have been constant  
since Pete Carroll succeeded Bill Parcells as coach of the 
Patriots. And Carroll has always finished second. 
</P>
<P>
	So it didn't matter to detractors that he led New England to two  
playoff berths in his two seasons, overcoming numerous injuries to 
do that. Reports surfaced that a bad performance Sunday against 
Jacksonville could put his job in serious jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll, who has three years left on his contract, didn't agree.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm coming back to put together a football team that can win  
the championship,'' he said after Sunday's 25-10 playoff loss to 
the Jaguars. ``With good health and good fortune, we'll do the 
things that we dream about doing and things that we set as our 
goals. And I'm going to be part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The player-friendly Carroll stepped into a difficult situation.  
Parcells, one of the NFL's top coaches, had just led the Patriots 
to the Super Bowl, then jumped to the New York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Patriots were 10-6 in Carroll's first season and only a  
one-point loss to Pittsburgh kept them from the AFC title game. 
They were 9-7 this season despite injuries to many key players, 
including Drew Bledsoe, Terry Glenn, Ted Johnson and Todd Collins, 
who all missed Sunday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet a few days after five other NFL coaches were fired, a member  
of the Patriots' front office reportedly planted a newspaper item 
last week that Carroll might be in trouble, according to a 
published report. 
</P>
<P>
	Linebacker Chris Slade said the Patriots were outplayed and  
outcoached in a 31-10 loss to Parcells and the New York Jets in the 
regular-season finale. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, though, Slade said, ``As far as I'm concerned, Pete  
Carroll's the head coach of the Patriots and that's the way it's 
going to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some veterans have spoken fondly of Parcells, a more assertive  
coach, but after the loss no Patriots criticized Carroll. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's fair'' to blame him, strong safety Lawyer  
Milloy said. ``All he does is prepare us to go out and play. He 
didn't think at the beginning of the year he was going to lose so 
many starters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All-Pro cornerback Ty Law, beaten by Jimmy Smith for a 37-yard  
scoring pass that put the Jaguars ahead 19-10 early in the fourth 
quarter, said coaching changes don't have to be disruptive. He 
cited the switch to Carroll as an example. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like Pete Carroll. I like Bill Parcells,'' Law said. ``We're  
getting to know him (Carroll). He's getting to know us a lot 
better. He's `The Man' on the team right now, so I have no doubt 
that he'll be back. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pete has 100 percent Ty Law's backing, if it means anything.''  
</P>
<P>
	``There's been a lot of talk about Pete, but Pete can't get out  
and play for us,'' wide receiver Shawn Jefferson said. ``Good game 
plans ... are put in place. It's up to these guys to execute the 
game plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, the only opinion that counts belongs to Patriots  
owner Robert Kraft, who had high praise for Carroll when the coach 
was hired. And Kraft has been silent publicly. 
</P>
<P>
	But Carroll said they've gotten along well,  
</P>
<P>
	``We've been together on everything we've done,'' Carroll said.  
``He has been terrific about it. ... Everything has been very 
amicable.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 17:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
