<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:30 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Jan. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Midwest Storm Spreads to Northeast  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicagoans are digging out from their biggest  
snow storm in more than 30 years while thousands of already delayed 
travelers across the Midwest and elsewhere are waiting for airlines 
to get their planes de-iced and back in the air. At least a dozen 
deaths are being blamed on the storm which pummeled the upper 
Midwest with more than a foot of snow and spread its dangerous 
driving conditions to the Northeast today. The southern flank of 
the storm carried tornadoes and severe thunderstorms into Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	Senators Say Clinton Will Survive  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Clinton is unlikely to be removed from  
office, but his presidency is permanently blighted by his 
impeachment on charges he lied about his affair with Monica 
Lewinsky, senators said today. Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and Sen. 
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., have floated a plan under which the 
Senate, after several days of hearing arguments, would vote on 
whether the charges are enough to remove the president from office. 
With a two-thirds majority unlikely, the Senate could move to end 
the trial and consider a censure motion against the president. 

</P>
<P>
	NASA Launches Mars Lander  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- A Mars lander equipped with an arm  
and shovel blasted off today on a 470 million-mile quest to uncover 
frozen water near the planet's South Pole. NASA's Mars Polar Lander 
soared aboard a Boeing rocket at exactly 3:21 p.m. The rain that 
managers had feared stayed away, allowing NASA to meet the 
instantaneous launch window despite an overcast sky. The Polar 
Lander is bound for the frosty fringes of Mars' south polar cap. 
It's due to arrive in December when it's late spring and the sun 
never sets. 

</P>
<P>
	Euro Trading Begins in Australia  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- International trading began today for the euro, the  
new common currency that is expected to increase Europe's power in 
the global economy and eventually rival the U.S. dollar as the type 
of money chosen by traders and reserves. The day's first dealings 
in the euro are expected to be cautious and subdued, and that was 
clear in Sydney, Australia, where trading began at 5 a.m. Monday (1 
p.m. EST Sunday). The 11 European nations that launched the euro 
represent 20 percent of world economic output. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Detains Denver Cult Members  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli police detained eight adults and six  
children belonging to a Denver-based apocalyptic Christian cult 
today, and accused the group of planning violent acts in Jerusalem. 
Police said the group planned to provoke a bloody shootout with 
Israeli cops which members of the group believe would hasten the 
Second Coming. ``They planned to carry out violent and extreme acts 
in the streets of Jerusalem at the end of 1999 to start the process 
of bringing Jesus back to life,'' said Israel's national police 
spokesman. 

</P>
<P>
	Survey: 1998 Was Less Violent Year  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The year ended with a war simmering between  
the United States and Iraq, but a cease-fire by Basque separatists 
and the end of Liberia's vicious civil war helped contribute to a 
sharp drop in the number of violent conflicts worldwide, think 
tanks reported today. In its annual survey, the National Defense 
Council Foundation counted 60 conflicts. That represents a drop of 
seven from 1997 but remains well above the 35 conflicts happening 
when the Cold War ended in 1989. The Alexandria, Va.-based council 
tallies all violent situations that result in regional instability. 

</P>
<P>
	Panthers Select Seifert as Coach  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- George Seifert, who has the best winning  
percentage of any coach in NFL history, will be the Carolina 
Panthers' new head coach, The Associated Press learned today. The 
team would not confirm its choice of Seifert to replace the fired 
Dom Capers, but sources said the Panthers were trying to arrange a 
news conference at Ericsson Stadium tomorrow to introduce their new 
coach. Seifert, who won 75.5 percent of his games (108-35) with San 
Francisco from 1989-96, did not immediately return telephone 
messages left at his home Sunday in Los Altos, Calif. 

</P>
<P>
	Moss Wins AP Offensive Rookie Award  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Randy Moss, the game-breaking wide receiver for  
the Minnesota Vikings, was a landslide winner of The Associated 
Press' NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year award today. Moss, who led 
the NFL with 17 touchdown receptions and averaged 19 yards per 
catch, received 44 votes from a nationwide panel of 47 sports 
writers and broadcasters. Indianapolis quarterback Peyton Manning, 
the top overall pick in the 1998 draft, got two votes. The other 
vote went to Jacksonville running back Fred Taylor. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
