<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bills Special-Teamer Pike Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Mark Pike, one of the Buffalo Bills'  
four remaining players from the Super Bowl years, retired Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pike, a special-teams standout, played his entire 13-year career  
with the Bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Joined by former Super Bowl teammates Andre Reed, Thurman Thomas  
and Bruce Smith in the media room at Ralph Wilson Stadium, a 
tearful Pike said he was retiring to spend more time with his 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I can be a full-time dad and a full-time husband,'' Pike  
said. ``My head and my heart say it's time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, Thomas and Smith are the only players left on the team who  
played in Buffalo's four straight Super Bowls losses from 1990-93. 
</P>
<P>
	As captain of special teams coverage, the 35-year-old Pike led  
the unit in tackles for the eighth time in nine years this season 
with 28. The Bills' season ended with a wild-card loss to Miami on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never would have imagined that I'd be part of one of the  
greatest runs in sports history,'' Pike said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
