<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: U.S., Sudan Make Contact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- The United States and Sudan are making quiet  
contacts to try to settle their differences, mainly over the U.S. 
missile attack that destroyed a factory in Khartoum, a leading Arab 
newspaper reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The London-based Al-Hayat quoted Sudanese Foreign Minister  
Mustafa Othman Ismael as saying he met with President Clinton on 
the sidelines of a U.N. General Assembly meeting and that the two 
men initiated the contacts. 
</P>
<P>
	It said Ismael had sought the meeting with Clinton to explain  
Sudan's position on the attack. He did not say when the meeting 
occurred, but Clinton made a speech at the opening of the General 
Assembly session on Sept. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. president understood the case, and he was positive as  
he ordered high-level State Department officials to continue the 
dialogue,'' Ismael was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Hayat said the U.S.-Sudan contacts are carried out through  
diplomatic channels, mainly between the two governments' 
representatives at the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. missiles severely damaged the Al-Shifa pharmaceutical  
factory in the Sudanese capital Khartoum on Aug. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	American forces fired the missiles at Sudan and at the suspected  
camps of Islamic extremists in Afghanistan in retaliation for twin 
bombings of U.S. embassies in East Africa on Aug. 7 that killed 224 
people, 12 of them Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States said that the factory was making ingredients  
for chemical weapons and had links to Saudi Arabian dissident Osama 
bin Laden, whose camps in Afghanistan were hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Sudan maintains that the plant made pharmaceuticals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 12:16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Twins Re-Sign Steinbach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Terry Steinbach has reached an agreement with  
the Minnesota Twins on a one-year contract with about $1 million, 
the Star Tribune reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 36-year-old catcher and Minnesota native turned down more  
money from the St. Louis Cardinals and Chicago White Sox to remain 
in his hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect to be back with the Twins next season,'' Steinbach  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The official announcement is expected Monday after the Twins  
create an opening for the veteran catcher on their 40-man roster. 
</P>
<P>
	In October, the Twins rejected an option to re-sign Steinbach  
for 1999 at $2.25 million and used their option to buy out his 
contract for $500,000. Just a week later, Steinbach filed for free 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinbach batted .242 with 14 home runs and 54 RBIs last season.  
</P>
</TEXT>
