<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 16:11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Thunderbird Concept Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                      *Ford Thunderbird Concept    	
</P>
<P>
	Classification: roadster.  
</P>
<P>
	Expected first production: 2001 model year.  
</P>
<P>
	Engine: 3.9-liter V8 from the 2000 Lincoln LS.  
</P>
<P>
	Transmission: five-speed automatic.  
</P>
<P>
	Features: removable hardtop with porthole windows and wraparound  
windshield are among the styling cues from the original 1955-57 
T-Birds. 
</P>
<P>
	Platform: built on chassis and major components of the Lincoln  
LS. 
</P>
<P>
	Assembly: Wixom, Mich., which will also produce the LS.  
</P>
<P>
	Expected price range: $35,000 to $45,000.  
</P>
<P>
	History: first T-Bird introduced in 1954 as '55 model; produced  
in various sizes until 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Interesting fact: President Kennedy so loved the '61 T-Bird that  
he included 50 of them in his inaugural procession. 
</P>
<P>
	Quote: ``The design of the Thunderbird concept reflects the  
attitude of a simpler time. The unbridled optimism and the 
confident attitude of the 1950s comes through in an absolutely 
modern design.'' --J Mays, Ford vice president of design. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 22:51:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDade's Career in Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SCRANTON, Pa. (AP) -- For Lois Fadden, all that mattered about  
the 36 years that Joseph McDade spent in Congress is this: He 
helped keep the work going at a local ammunition plant that 
employed her brother-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
	Never mind the eight-year racketeering case that cast a cloud  
over McDade's career before the Pennsylvania Republican finally won 
acquittal in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor do constituents ponder over the derisive comment about the  
$66 million he got from federal taxpayers to build the Steamtown 
railroad historic site from scratch in Scranton, about 100 miles 
north of Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	They sent him back to Washington 18 times, and no one doubts  
they would have given him a 19th two-year House term, too, had the 
67-year-old lawmaker not elected to retire. For the folks in 
Scranton, it was the bread-and-butter issues that mattered. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you voted for him, you voted for yourself, too,'' Ms.  
Fadden said. ``He kept a lot of people working, raising families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDade, the House's senior Republican, used his spot on the  
defense spending panel to make sure a local factory kept getting 
contracts to produce howitzer shells. He also helped businesses 
battle federal bureaucracy and lured defense companies to replace a 
collapsed coal industry. 
</P>
<P>
	His supporters say most people outside the district heard only  
one side of McDade, the one presented in the national media. 
</P>
<P>
	``They probably know more about the trial and Steamtown,'' said  
J.A. Panuska, former president of the University of Scranton. 
``They are missing the solid, devoted worker who is a person of 
integrity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDade was cleared in August 1996 of federal charges that he  
accepted $100,000 in vacations, gifts and campaign contributions in 
exchange for helping defense contractors inside and outside his 
district win $68 million in contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Although McDade was acquitted, the ordeal took a political and  
personal toll. He lost the chance to become chairman of the 
powerful House Appropriations Committee. He also was diagnosed with 
Parkinson's disease, which causes a slow but steady loss of motor 
skills and flexibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, his efforts to create the Steamtown site became a  
symbol of pork-barrel politics to critics. Local business leaders, 
however, consider the federally financed project an important 
economic development tool. 
</P>
<P>
	McDade's accomplishments in the district are numerous, and many  
buildings, a recreational trail and a park built atop an abandoned 
coal mine bear his name. 
</P>
<P>
	McDade entered Congress in 1963 and became a member of the  
Appropriations Committee two years later, becoming adept at 
bringing millions of dollars to Scranton and environs. 
</P>
<P>
	When President Reagan called for more defense spending in the  
early 1980s, McDade saw job opportunities and joined the 
committee's defense panel, rising to the ranking Republican in 
1985. It was in that capacity where he had the most influence on 
national issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Joe McDade is a very strong person, and if there's something  
he wanted to see accomplished or prevent, he didn't give in 
easily,'' said Rep. Bill Young, R-Fla., incoming chairman of the 
Appropriations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	McDade's office was renowned for constituent service, helping  
people fill out unemployment claims and resolve Social Security 
disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	McDade rarely sought headlines or television appearances and  
never sought any higher office. He usually won re-election by wide 
margins, even while criminal charges were pending against him. 
</P>
<P>
	His efforts to help defense firms win contracts ultimately got  
him in trouble. Federal prosecutors tried to link those contracts 
to free flights he received on corporate jets, tickets to the NCAA 
Final Four basketball tournament and other gifts. 
</P>
<P>
	On the witness stand in Philadelphia, McDade acknowledged  
receiving many of the items, but he blamed staff oversight for his 
failure to report them. The jury cleared him. 
</P>
<P>
	A few weeks later, defense contractors and other supporters  
threw a poolside cocktail party for McDade at the Republican 
National Convention in San Diego. Later, he invited jurors to 
Washington for a private tour of the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	McDade, who said he wanted to spend more time with his family,  
has not announced any post-retirement plans. He said his eight 
years under investigation and indictment were his only 
disappointments in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very privileged to have served here,'' he said. ``I have  
been able to move the wheel a number of times in helping the 
country.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 11:12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spurrier Defuses QB Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Less than 12 hours after Florida's Orange Bowl win  
over Syracuse, coach Steve Spurrier was subtly turning up the heat 
on Doug Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurrier said Sunday that Johnson, who broke his left leg midway  
through the seventh-ranked Gators' 31-10 victory, would remain his 
No. 1 quarterback ahead of Jesse Palmer when spring practice 
begins. 
</P>
<P>
	``Doug is first in line to be our quarterback next year,''  
Spurrier said before going on recruiting visits. ``Hopefully we 
won't have to alternate them. We're not planning on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, that could change based on Johnson's ability to  
recover in time for spring ball. Or his decision whether to 
concentrate on football this summer instead of playing minor-league 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know how all of this is going to play out,'' Spurrier  
said. ``Doug's got to make a decision whether to stay in 
Gainesville all summer. It helps a quarterback to be a team leader 
if he's with them working out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A third baseman in the Tampa Bay system, Johnson was rated the  
Devil Rays' 10th-best prospect by Baseball America magazine before 
rotator-cuff surgery caused him to sit out last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll talk to some people, talk to the Devil Rays,'' Johnson  
said Saturday night. He expects to make a decision in about a 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson appeared on the way to his best game of the season  
before getting injured on a hit by Syracuse's Marc Pilon with 4:18 
left before halftime. X-rays showed a broken fibula, requiring 
about 12 weeks of rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson completed his first six passes for 139 yards and  
touchdown tosses of 51 and 26 yards to Travis Taylor, finishing 
12-of-17 for 195 yards. That came after a regular season in which 
he threw for 2,346 yards with 19 TDs and only eight interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Doug's got one year left of college football,'' Spurrier said.  
``If baseball's his best sport, he's got the rest of his life to do 
that. He's only got one more year to see if football's his best 
sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer, whose broken collarbone gave Johnson the starting job  
midway through the season, completed 10 of 14 for 113 yards and a 
TD against the 18th-ranked Orangemen. 
</P>
<P>
	``He understands, he'll be fine,'' said Spurrier, who had the  
duo alternating plays for the first five games this year. ``He'll 
be ready to go when called upon.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 18:32:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avalanche Kills Two Teens in Utah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANTI, Utah (AP) -- The bodies of two teen-age boys who were  
killed in an avalanche while snowboarding were found early Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The boys, whose names were not released, were reported missing  
late Saturday night by their fathers, Sanpete County sheriff's 
dispatcher Jody Pace said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the boys, 16 and 17 years old, were buried in a  
snowdrift that broke loose and descended 150 feet in Fairview 
Canyon, about 100 miles south of Salt Lake City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
