<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Md. Farmer Seeks Profit From Deers / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TANEYTOWN, Md. (AP) -- To most farmers, deer are a pest that eat  
their crops. But Leonard Miller thinks that raising deer for their 
meat could be a profitable business. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller faces considerable odds not only in the skeptical farm  
community but in the Legislature as well. Maryland is one of three 
states that prohibit deer farming. 
</P>
<P>
	Deer devoured an estimated $38 million worth of corn, wheat and  
soybeans in the state in 1996, according to a survey by the 
University of Maryland. That did not include damage to other 
vegetables and fruit. 
</P>
<P>
	``They take a look at the wild deer here and think these are the  
same, but these animals, the way they're grouped up and treated, is 
just the same as beef or dairy cattle would be,'' Miller told The 
(Baltimore) Sun recently. 
</P>
<P>
	There is a growing market for venison among gourmet restaurants  
and grocery stores and health-conscious meat lovers seeking to cut 
back on fat and cholesterol. Miller thinks deer could give his farm 
a boost. 
</P>
<P>
	Venison consumption in the United States has risen 30 percent a  
year for the past five years, said Barbara Fox, executive director 
of the North American Deer Farmers Association. More than 80 
percent of that meat comes from New Zealand, which is the major 
exporter worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Deer farming caught on in the United States in the 1970s,  
starting with two farmers who began raising European species such 
as fallow and red deer. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, who has three teen-age children, hopes domesticated deer  
could be the product that ensures his farm's viability into the 
next generation. 
</P>
<P>
	He used to raise dairy cattle but has sold off his herd over the  
past few years. Fluctuating milk prices and the labor-intensive 
nature of dairy farming convinced him it would not ensure the farm 
for his children. 
</P>
<P>
	His son, Leonard Jr., 19, works as a hunting guide in Montana.  
It was while on such a trip two years ago that he met John Craig, a 
Maine farmer who raises deer. He told his father about it. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Miller ordered several deer from Craig, but as he  
looked into state regulations he learned he could be breaking the 
law if he penned the deer on his farm. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller had hoped to get the Maryland Farm Bureau to include a  
proposal on deer in its legislative agenda for the coming 
legislative session, but the organization rejected the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	The Farm Bureau was concerned about diseases the animals can  
spread to existing livestock herds, such as cattle, said Emily 
Wilson, the group's assistant director of government relations. 
</P>
<P>
	But Miller maintains that deer can be managed and inoculated  
like any other farm animal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 15:45:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Questions Abound About NBA Lockout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- We should know shortly whether David Stern's  
threat was real, whether Michael Jordan will play again and whether 
it was worth it to push the NBA to the brink of calamity. 
</P>
<P>
	Stern is due back in the office Monday after spending two weeks  
in Aspen, Colo., and union director Billy Hunter has told the 
players on his negotiating committee to be in town by Tuesday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're ready to negotiate. The league is refusing to  
negotiate,'' Hunter said Sunday. Hunter also said he had not yet 
spoken to Stern. 
</P>
<P>
	With Thursday the deadline for reaching a new collective  
bargaining agreement, a look at some of the most pressing questions 
in what will be one of the most pivotal weeks in NBA history. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: They wouldn't cancel the rest of the season, would they?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Yes, they would. The threat of losing the entire 1998-99  
season is very real, with Stern saying many owners are pushing him 
to pull the plug and teach everyone a lesson about how seriously 
imperiled the league's financial health is. But rest assured, NBA 
fans, Stern will not cancel the season without making at least one 
sincere, last-ditch effort to forge a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: So when does Stern make his final push?  
</P>
<P>
	A: It depends on what his owners tell him to do. One possibility  
would be for him to come out of the Board of Governors meeting 
Thursday with the authorization to make one ``absolute, final 
offer.'' It's hard to see Stern ending the season without something 
being voted on by the 430 players. The NHL lockout settlement in 
1995 came several days after the deadline, and baseball owners went 
two days past their deadline when they canceled the 1994 World 
Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What is the biggest factor in the way of a compromise?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Aside from the fact that the chief negotiators have let this  
fight get too personal, the single biggest stumbling block appears 
to be the union's insistence upon receiving 57 percent of the 
revenues in year 6 of a six-year agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: So why doesn't the union drop to 56 percent?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Because the players received 57 percent last season, and  
union director Billy Hunter has said that even though the players 
are willing to take less in years 4 and 5 of the agreement, they 
shouldn't come out of year 6 receiving any less of a percentage 
than they had when they negotiated the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: How far apart are they after so many proposals and  
counterproposals? 
</P>
<P>
	A: Each side has addressed the other's main concerns, with the  
union limiting high-end salaries and the owners offering higher pay 
for the so-called shrinking middle-class of the player population. 
The main sticking point now is the percentage of revenues that 
should be devoted to salaries, the owners asking for 53-54 percent 
and the players asking for 55-57 percent. Each percentage point 
equals about $20 million annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Who is most to blame?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Both sides. The owners could have gotten a deal done months  
ago by playing the give-and-take negotiating game more 
aggressively. The union, for its part, should have found a way to 
make a deal Oct. 28 when Stern still wanted to save an 82-game 
season, or during the 30-day period late in the summer when 
everyone was waiting for arbitrator John Feerick's guaranteed 
contracts ruling. Once regular-season games became irretrievably 
lost, there was no chance for a quick compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What happens if they settle?  
</P>
<P>
	A: First, they'd have to put the agreement on paper and have it  
ratified -- a process that could take about a week. After that, 
training camps would open, 200 free agents would be on the market, 
trades could take place and everyone would be placed into an 
unprecedented scramble before the season started in early February. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What happens if they don't settle?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Everything becomes chaotic. Franchises that are worth an  
average of $200 million lose value, $1 billion in player salaries 
goes unpaid, someone tries to start a new league, players try to 
make money overseas, the union decertifies, the whole mess is 
fought in court, the fans continue to learn to live without the NBA 
and the league never is the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What's wrong with them?  
</P>
<P>
	A: The owners and the commissioner have been waiting several  
years to regain control of their industry and set the NBA on the 
correct financial course. Kevin Garnett signed for $126 million in 
1997, and Allen Iverson may have topped that figure in 1998 if the 
lockout hadn't commenced. As far as they're concerned, this fight 
had to be fought at some point in time to put a stop to the lunacy. 
The players, meanwhile, know that they are the product everyone 
pays to see. And like any union, it does not want to give back many 
of the gains they have made at the bargaining table through the 
years. Don't forget that players are competitors. And when someone 
challenges them, they fight back harder than most. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What about the fans?  
</P>
<P>
	A: The widespread public apathy associated with this lockout  
proves that fans don't want to take sides on an issue in which no 
one seems to have their best interests at heart. The fan population 
has become jaded by strikes and lockouts in major league baseball, 
pro football and pro hockey during the past three decades, and it 
appears they have learned to tune out when billionaires and 
millionaires fight over their money. If the lockout ends and a 45- 
to 50-game season is saved, there's no telling if and when the fans 
will come back. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: And finally, what about Jordan?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Only Michael knows, and it'll take a settlement to get him to  
announce his plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 19:42:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Midwest Digs Out From Winter Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicagoans dug out from their biggest snowstorm  
in more than 30 years Sunday while thousands of already delayed 
travelers across the Midwest waited for airlines to get their 
planes de-iced and back in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	About 22 inches of snow had piled up from Chicago across  
northern Indiana as the storm spread snow, ice, slush and rain from 
the Missouri Valley to the East Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Old Man Winter can just go away now and give us  
80-degree weather. He made his point,'' Karen Erickson said after 
finding her car covered by a snow drift in Fond du Lac, Wis., 60 
miles north of Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 28 deaths had been blamed on the storm, 10 of them in  
Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago's Lakeshore Drive reopened and pavement was clean on  
many other main arteries. However, public and Catholic school 
classes were canceled for Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going real well considering that 24 hours ago we were in  
the second-worst snowstorm in Chicago history,'' said Terry Levin, 
a spokesman for the city, which put more than 700 pieces of 
snow-fighting equipment on the streets. The city's record is 23 
inches, set in 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	However, U.S. Rep. Bobby Rush, who's running against Mayor  
Richard Daley in February, complained that crews concentrated on 
neighborhoods with more white residents. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not about politics,'' Daley responded.  
</P>
<P>
	The city's delay in plowing away the 18.8 inches that fell in  
1979 was blamed for Jane Byrne's upset victory over incumbent Mayor 
Michael Bilandic in that year's Democratic primary. 
</P>
<P>
	The ice and blinding, wind-driven snow created havoc for air  
travelers through the entire weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	At Chicago's O'Hare International Airport, the nation's busiest,  
United, American and most other airlines canceled the bulk of their 
flights Saturday. And on Sunday -- expected to be one of the busiest 
travel days of the year -- United canceled 60 percent of its flights 
out of Chicago and American canceled at least half, according to 
officials at the airport's two largest carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sherri Gilbert waited in a line the length of two football  
fields at O'Hare's United terminal. She had been trying to get home 
to Springfield, Mo., from Portland, Maine, since Friday night and 
her chances of making a flight Sunday were grim. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't get through this line before my flight leaves,'' said  
Gilbert, one of the lucky ones who got a hotel room near O'Hare 
Saturday night. ``I told my husband one more day and I'm going to 
have to go shopping in Chicago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The effects of Chicago's woes spread far beyond the city.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone wants to go to Chicago to get somewhere else,'' said  
Kathy Tremmel of Harlan, Iowa, who was stuck at Omaha's Eppley 
Airfield trying to catch a connecting flight in Chicago to take her 
to London. 
</P>
<P>
	Indianapolis International Airport closed overnight for the  
first time in 20 years. Milwaukee's Mitchell International Airport 
reopened Sunday after being shut down overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight cancellations at Detroit Metropolitan Airport left  
travelers sacked out in booths at Mike &AMP; Pat's Bar &AMP; Deli -- which 
advertised ``Best view of the snow inside the airport'' -- while 
others slept in an airport mezzanine. The airport doled out about 
2,000 pillows and 2,200 blankets, airport spokesman Mike Conway 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like one big pajama party,'' said Donna Brigman. She  
and her 13-year-old daughter returned to Detroit on Saturday from a 
Florida vacation -- they swam with dolphins in temperatures in the 
80s -- but couldn't find a way home to Ypsilanti, just 20 miles 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10 to 15 inches of snow that blanketed the Detroit  
metropolitan area was the most from a winter storm since Jan. 6, 
1994, the National Weather Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	A stretch of Interstate 65 in northwestern Indiana was closed  
Sunday for the second time in two days, and 10 cities and 44 of the 
state's 92 counties still banned unnecessary travel. Drifts more 
than 2 feet high closed the South Shore Railroad, which carries 
over 12,000 daily commuters from northwestern Indiana to Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The roads were like ice,'' said John Rawlings, who spent the  
night with 200 other travelers at Faith Baptist Church near 
Lafayette, Ind., after his van slid off I-65. ``The wind just 
picked it up and put it in the ditch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four people were killed and as many as 23 others were injured  
Sunday in a 16-vehicle accident on ice-slicked Interstate 81 in 
Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm also spread ice on parts of the Northeast. Ice was  
blamed for a 50-car pileup on New York's Grand Central Parkway, and 
22 cars and a truck were caught in a chain-reaction wreck on I-80 
in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Flooding forced authorities to close the Garden State Parkway in  
New Jersey on Sunday when a stream covered the roadway about 10 
miles northwest of Newark. It was later reopened. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain drenched New York City, where 2.42 inches of rain fell in  
Central Park, breaking the record of 1.41 inches for the date set 
in 1936. Bridgeport, Conn., also set a record with 2 inches of 
rain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
