<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: BMW Chief Admits Mistakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMBURG, Germany (AP) -- BMW chairman Bernd Pischetsrieder  
acknowledged management errors at Rover Group, the company's 
struggling British subsidiary, according to a report released 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	BMW has Rover on ``too long a leash,'' Pischetsrieder was quoted  
as saying in the Hamburg-based weekly newsmagazine Der Spiegel. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Rover's nagging financial woes -- analysts predict the  
unit could post losses of $650 million for 1998 -- the BMW chief 
declared he has no plans to resign. There has been speculation that 
BMW board member Wolfgang Reitzle would replace Pischetsrieder as 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Rover failed to sell enough cars in Britain to private  
customers, although sales remained strong to groups such as car 
rental agencies, the BMW chief said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several top managers have resigned over the crisis at Rover,  
which reached agreement with unions in December to trim 2,500 jobs 
from the current work force of 39,000. 
</P>
<P>
	BMW's Rolls Royce subsidiary also expects to post 1998 losses of  
$179 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Pischetsrieder denied any plans for a merger. ``Under no  
circumstances will we hand Rolls Royce over to Volkswagen or anyone 
else,'' he was quoted as saying. Rumors had named VW and Ford as 
possible merger partners with Bayerische Motoren Werke AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Offsetting losses in its subsidiaries, the BMW brand expects  
record profits this year of $1.9 billion, according to recent 
German media reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
