<HEADLINE> Kona Gold Sets Santa Anita Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Kona Gold broke the Santa Anita track  
record for 5 1/2 furlongs when the 5-year-old gelding won the $107,300 
El Conejo Handicap in 1:01 3-5, beating Big Jag by 2 1/4 lengths 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Alex Solis, Kona Gold knocked a fifth of a second off  
the record set by Lit De Justice in the 1996 El Conejo. 
</P>
<P>
	Kona Gold, who carried high weight of 119 pounds, paid $4, $2.60  
and $2.20. Big Jag returned $3.40 and $2.40. Mr. Doubledown was 
another 4 1/2 lengths back, and paid $2.40 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory, worth $64,380, increased Kona Gold's career  
earnings to $282,514, with four wins in seven starts. He was third 
last year in the Breeders' Cup Sprint. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the week, Bruce Headley, who trains Kona Gold, had  
suggested his horse would set a track record. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's training out of his mind,'' Headley said.  
</P>
<P>
	``When Bruce says something like a horse is going to set a track  
record, I know I take him seriously,'' Solis said. ``I knew this 
horse had never trained as well as he had before this race. So I 
was confident, too.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
