<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Plunge at Midday Close / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was sharply lower against the yen  
Monday as the euro made a quiet debut on Asian foreign exchange 
markets. Fears about a stronger yen caused Tokyo share prices to 
plunge in the first trading session of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 113.28 yen at midday, down 1.92 yen from late  
Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its New York level of 113.57 yen 
late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 426.28 points,  
or 3.08 percent, to close the abbreviated session at 13,415.89 
points. On Wednesday, the average closed down 1.84 points, or 0.17 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Tokyo were closed Thursday and Friday for  
the New Year's holidays. The Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at the end 
of morning trading Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	At midday Monday, the euro was quoted at dlrs 1.1800, up from  
dlrs 1.1755 earlier in the session, and well above the fixing rate 
of dlrs 1.16675 set Thursday by the European Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro also reached 134.77 yen at midday, above 132.60 earlier  
and up from its initial fixing of 132.80 yen Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Demand for euros by Japanese investors wanting to acquire  
euro-denominated assets pushed the currency up against the yen, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, many players were reluctant to trade the new currency  
against either the dollar or the yen ahead of the opening of the 
European market later Monday, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the first week, it will be all wait-and-see,'' said  
Kazuo Takayama, chief foreign exchange sales manager at Midland 
Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Takashi Nakauchi, foreign exchange manager at Bank of  
Tokyo-Mitsubishi, said he arrived at the trading room at 4 a.m. to 
make sure systems were functioning properly. 
</P>
<P>
	No banks have reported any major system glitches so far.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, worries about the state of U.S. and Latin American  
financial markets continued to exert downward pressure on the 
dollar, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Tokyo share prices fell amid active  
futures-led selling because of concern over a steep gain in the yen 
against the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	``Players are worried about a continued decline of the dollar  
and uncertain outlook for the U.S. economy,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, 
general manager at Tokyo Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Among early losers were blue chips, including Sony, NEC,  
Fujitsu, Toyota Motor and Honda Motor. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen tends to make Japanese exports more expensive  
abroad, thus cutting into earnings of export-oriented companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 22.07 points, or 2.03 percent, to close at 
1,064.92. The TOPIX finished down 1.84 points or 0.17 percent, on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.990 percent from Wednesday's finish of 2.010 
percent, driving its price up to 98.48 yen from 98.33 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
