<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Jan. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Report: Dole To Leave Red Cross  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole is planning to step aside as  
president of the American Red Cross in a step her political 
supporters hope will lead to her running for president, Newsweek 
magazine reported. The magazine reports in its Jan. 11 edition that 
one of Mrs. Dole's close advisers described her decision as a 
``first step'' toward a possible campaign for the Republican 
nomination. Red Cross officials would not confirm the report but 
announced late today that Mrs. Dole would make a ``major'' 
announcement tomorrow. Mrs. Dole's husband, former Sen. Bob Dole, 
was the GOP presidential nominee in 1996 and she has consistently 
scored high in public opinion polls as a potential candidate. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Backs Long-Term Care Credit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is proposing an  
unprecedented $1,000 tax credit, at a cost of billions, to 
compensate 2 million American families struggling to provide 
long-term care for elderly or disabled relatives. The tax credit, 
meant to compensate caregivers for a wide range of activities that 
tending to others requires, is part of a five-year, $6.2 billion 
package that the president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton 
will announce tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Deadly Storm Strikes Midwest  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- At least 23 deaths are being blamed on the storm  
that's spread snow, ice, slush and rain from the Missouri Valley to 
the East Coast. Ten of the deaths were in Illinois. Chicago got 
almost 22 inches of snow, its biggest snowfall since 1967. The 
storm also hit the Northeast, where ice caused numerous car 
crashes. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Case May Move Quickly  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Momentum is building for a Senate plan that  
may lead to the censure of President Clinton. Proposed by one 
Democrat and one Republican, the proposal would give the House 
prosecutors and the White House each one day to present the senate 
with their cases. Senators would then have a day to ask questions. 
Then, on the fourth day, they would vote on whether charges against 
the president, even if true, were grave enough to remove him from 
office. If a two-thirds majority isn't reached, the Senate could 
adjourn the trial with a simple majority, then move to a possible 
censure motion against the president. 

</P>
<P>
	Mars Probe Starts 11-Month Trip  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- A Mars lander is up and away at Cape  
Canaveral, headed for the fringes of the Martian south polar cap 
470 million miles away. NASA's Mars Polar Lander took off aboard a 
Boeing rocket at exactly 3:21 p.m. The rain that managers had 
feared stayed away, allowing NASA to meet the instantaneous launch 
window despite an overcast sky. The lander is due to arrive in 
December when it's late spring on Mars and the sun never sets. 

</P>
<P>
	Euro Trading Begins  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The euro, the new common currency expected to  
increase Europe's power in the global economy, began trading today. 
The day's first dealings in the euro were expected to be cautious 
and subdued, and that was clear in Sydney, Australia, where the 
currency was trading between $1.1742 and $1.1777. In Tokyo, the new 
currency was trading from $1.1700 to $1.1748. The 11 European 
nations that launched the euro represent 20 percent of world 
economic output. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Detains Christian Cult  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli police today detained eight adults and  
six children belonging to a Denver-based Christian Cult they say 
planned to open fire on officers in Jerusalem at the end of 1999. 
``They planned to carry out violent and extreme acts in the streets 
of Jerusalem at the end of 1999 to start the process of bringing 
Jesus back to life,'' said Israel's national police spokesman. 

</P>
<P>
	`Patch Adams' Tops Box Office Again  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Patch Adams'' was the No. 1 movie for a  
second weekend, and ``Stepmom'' held its own as family films 
claimed the top box office spots over the New Year's holiday, 
according to weekly industry estimates released today. Though 
roundly panned as sappy, the Robin Williams movie about a doctor 
who uses comedy to heal was an audience hit with $20.1 million in 
ticket sales. ``Stepmom,'' which also took critical lumps, was 
second with $15 million, followed by the Tom Hanks-Meg Ryan comedy 
``You've Got Mail'' with $14.1 million. 

</P>
<P>
	It's Jets vs. Jaguars Next Sunday  
</P>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The Jacksonville Jaguars beat the New  
England Patriots 25-10 in the AFC wild-card playoffs today. With 
the win, the Jaguars travel to New York to play the Jets next 
Sunday. It will mark coach Tom Coughlin's first meeting with his 
old mentor, Bill Parcells, since the Jaguars lost to the 
Parcells-coached Patriots in the 1996 AFC Championship game. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JAKE ULICK  
</P>
