<HEADLINE> Hurt Disney Tourist Leaves Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORANGE, Calif. (AP) -- A Washington state tourist was released  
from the hospital more than a week after she suffered head injuries 
in a Disneyland accident that killed her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	Lieu Thuy Vuong was discharged from University of California,  
Irvine Medical Center on Saturday, a few days earlier than planned, 
said Michelle Glassmeyer, a spokeswoman for the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Vuong, 43, of Duvall, Wash., underwent minor reconstructive  
surgery on the right side of her face following the Christmas Eve 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	She and her husband, Luan Phi Dawson, were in a crowd waiting to  
board the Columbia -- Disneyland's replica of a three-masted sailing 
ship -- when a mooring rope tightened and tore an 8-pound, T-shaped 
metal cleat from the ship's bow. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawson, 33, suffered severe head injuries and died two days  
later at UCI Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first deadly accident at Disneyland since 1984 and  
the ninth since the park opened in 1955. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 19:11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bell Atlantic Confirms Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bell Atlantic Corp. and AirTouch Communications  
Inc. confirmed they are holding talks relating to a possible 
business combination. 
</P>
<P>
	AirTouch, the nation's second-largest cellular phone company,  
said that ``significant issues still remain unresolved,'' and that 
its board of directors had not approved a transaction. It did not 
elaborate further. 
</P>
<P>
	In statements released late Sunday, both companies said that no  
further comment would be made by either company until an agreement 
had been reached or discussions were terminated. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Thursday cable news channel CNBC, citing sources close to  
the talks, said that Bell Atlantic was negotiating a $45 billion 
takeover of AirTouch. The reported purchase price would make Bell 
Atlantic-AirTouch the fifth-largest merger in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Gerace, a Bell Atlantic spokesman, refused to comment on the  
report, nor would he comment on a possible timetable for a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Bell Atlantic this summer agreed to merge with  
GTE Corp. in a $64 billion deal that would allow the companies to 
create a huge provider of all-in-one services, including long 
distance, local calling and wireless services. 
</P>
<P>
	CNBC said the Stamford, Conn.-based GTE has already agreed to  
the AirTouch deal, which would be completed before the Bell 
Atlantic-GTE deal closes. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco-based AirTouch, a spinoff of former Baby Bell  
Pacific Telesis Group, ranks behind only AT&AMP;T Corp. among U.S. 
cellular phone companies. The company has 14 million cellular 
subscribers in the United States, as well as fast-growing 
international operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell Atlantic, the nation's biggest local phone company, has 42  
million telephone access lines and 8 million wireless customers 
worldwide. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 14:15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Patch Adams' Tops Box Office Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Patch Adams'' was the No. 1 movie for a  
second weekend and ``Stepmom'' held its own as family films claimed 
the top box office spots over the New Year's holiday, according to 
industry estimates Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Though roundly panned as sappy, the Robin Williams movie about a  
doctor who uses comedy to heal was an audience hit with $20.1 
million in ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are really responding to his Golden Globe nomination  
for best actor and they're very taken by ... the true-life story of 
Patch Adams,'' said Alan Sutton, senior vice president of 
distribution and marketing for Universal Pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stepmom,'' which also took critical lumps, was second with $15  
million, followed by the Tom Hanks-Meg Ryan comedy ``You've Got 
Mail'' with $14.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Without any new competition -- not a single film debuted in wide  
release -- animated and children's films held their own. Studios 
truck out such fare for the holidays because they know families 
tend to get together and the children are out of school. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Prince of Egypt,'' DreamWorks' animated adult fable of  
Moses that reportedly cost more than $100 million to make, was in 
fourth place with $11.5 million, according to Exhibitor Relations 
Co. Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Final figures were to be released Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Disney's ``A Bug's Life'' had legs -- many of them. In fifth  
place, it lost just 1 percent of its audience in its seventh week 
for a $10 million gross. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney had two other films in the Top 10. The big ape movie  
``Mighty Joe Young'' was sixth with $8.7 million and ``Enemy of the 
State'' was at No. 8 with $5 million, behind the horror film ``The 
Faculty,'' which took in $8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Star Trek: Insurrection'' and ``Jack Frost'' rounded out the  
list, with $4.8 million and $3.2 million, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	In its seventh week, ``Enemy of the State'' was close to hitting  
the $100 million total gross already exceeded by four other Disney 
films of 1998: ``A Bug's Life,'' ``Waterboy,'' ``Armageddon'' and 
``Mulan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Disney expects to have well over $1.1 billion in North  
American grosses for the box office year running from Jan. 5, 1998 
through Sunday. That would put it ahead even of Paramount, which 
scored with the blockbuster ``Titanic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a titanic comeback, or actually a comeback from  
`Titanic,''' quipped Phil Barlow, president of Disney's Buena Vista 
Pictures Distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the decade of the '90s, this will be the fifth time that  
this studio has finished first in box office share,'' he said. ``We 
have been No.1 or No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd bottle it if I could. If I knew what was going on I'd be  
really rich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Movies are thriving generally, thanks in part to the soaring  
number of screens, Barlow added. 
</P>
<P>
	``All sorts of records are being shattered. People are going to  
movies more than they've ever gone ... and you've got the 
megaplexes,'' he said. ``God movies and good theaters -- it's kind 
of an unbeatable combination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the take for the top 12 weekend films was down from the  
same weekend last year -- $106.4 million compared to $107.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Several films opened in limited release to qualify for Oscar  
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing by Heart,'' an ensemble romance starring Sean Connery,  
Gena Rowlands, Angelina Jolie and Gillian Anderson of ``The 
X-Files,'' had a strong $28,000 on a single screen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Hi-Lo Country,'' a Western with Woody Harrelson, had a  
meager $6,363 on three screens. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shakespeare in Love,'' the literate, fictional tale of how the  
Bard got his inspiration, was on track to be the year's first 
sleeper hit. Although it finished out of the top 10, the movie 
earned $3.2 million in its fourth weekend, a 23 percent increase 
over the previous weekend. The 299 locations where it was shown 
took in more than $10,700, on average. 
</P>
<P>
	The war film ``The Thin Red Line,'' playing on just two screens,  
had $376,326 in ticket sales, jumping an enormous 68 percent in its 
second weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, the well-reviewed ``Down in the Delta,'' the  
first directing effort of noted author Maya Angelou, was tanking 
even though it played on just two screens, with ticket sales down 
27 percent in its second weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are estimated grosses at North American theaters for Friday  
through Sunday as compiled by Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc.: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Patch Adams,'' $20.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Stepmom,'' $15 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``You've Got Mail,'' $14.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``The Prince of Egypt,'' $11.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``A Bug's Life,'' $10 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Mighty Joe Young,'' $8.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``The Faculty,'' $8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Enemy of the State,'' $5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Star Trek: Insurrection,'' $4.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``Jack Frost,'' $3.2 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
