<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 15:35:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Look at 3 DaimlerChrysler Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler AG unveiled three concept vehicles Sunday at the  
North American International Auto Show media preview in Detroit. A 
fourth, the Jeep Commander, debuted last week at the Los Angeles 
auto show. A look at each: 

</P>
<P>
                         *CHRYSLER CITADEL   	
</P>
<P>
	Classification: sedan.  
</P>
<P>
	Passengers: five.  
</P>
<P>
	Powertrain: hybrid using 3.5-liter V6 to drive rear wheels with  
electric motor to drive front wheels. 
</P>
<P>
	Transmission: four-speed automatic.  
</P>
<P>
	Features: powertrain designed to get V8 power from a V6, with 4  
mpg better mileage than a conventional V8; dual power-sliding rear 
doors and retractable rear cargo door that slides under the floor 
for better access to back seat and cargo area; four-wheel drive. 

</P>
<P>
                         *DODGE CHARGER R/T   	
</P>
<P>
	Classification: sedan.  
</P>
<P>
	Passengers: four.  
</P>
<P>
	Engine: 4.7-liter, supercharged V8 that runs on compressed  
natural gas. 
</P>
<P>
	Transmission: five-speed manual.  
</P>
<P>
	Features: 325 horsepower from clean natural-gas powered engine;  
gas stored in new tank system that takes up less space but could 
deliver 300-mile driving range. 

</P>
<P>
                         *DODGE POWER WAGON   	
</P>
<P>
	Classification: pickup truck.  
</P>
<P>
	Passengers: three.  
</P>
<P>
	Engine: 7.2-liter, direct-injection, turbocharged diesel six.  
</P>
<P>
	Transmission: four-speed automatic.  
</P>
<P>
	Features: Engine designed to run on clean-burning, sulfur-free  
``designer'' fuel being developed by Syntroleum Corp.; four-wheel 
drive. 

</P>
<P>
                          *JEEP COMMANDER   	
</P>
<P>
	Classification: sport utility vehicle.  
</P>
<P>
	Passengers: five.  
</P>
<P>
	Engine: electric fuel-cell (not yet functional).  
</P>
<P>
	Features: designed to run on methanol, which would be converted  
onboard to the hydrogen that the fuel cell would combine with 
oxygen to create electricity. 

</P>
</TEXT>
