<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Debt Moves Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler has delayed the planned  
consolidation of its two financial services divisions while it 
evaluates the businesses on which the merged unit should focus, an 
executive said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	When Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler Corp. merged in November,  
co-chairman Robert J. Eaton said an announcement about the 
consolidation of Chrysler Financial Corp. and Daimler's debis would 
be made in December. 
</P>
<P>
	But Thomas T. Stallkamp, president of DaimlerChrysler's North  
American operations, said the complexity of the consolidation has 
slowed it down. He declined to reveal the new target date. 
</P>
<P>
	While Chrysler Financial is involved only in automotive  
financing, debis is diversified with business in such areas as 
train systems and insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Debis is in lots of businesses, so we're trying to see how to  
focus it and determine which businesses to stay in,'' Stallkamp 
said during in an interview at the North American International 
Auto Show. 
</P>
<P>
	Work on consolidating the automotive financing side of the  
business is virtually completed, he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
