<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Jan. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Snow, Ice Affect Midwest Travel  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A huge snowstorm blew across the Midwest on  
Saturday with whiteout conditions and drifts up to 8 feet high, 
canceling hundreds of airline flights, forcing motorists off roads 
and keeping mail deliverers from their appointed rounds. By 
Saturday evening, the storm had dumped 17 inches at Chicago's 
Midway Airport, 12 inches in Milwaukee and 11 inches on Detroit 
Metropolitan Airport in Romulus. It was 13 inches deep in western 
Indiana's Parke County, and 10 inches of new snow had fallen in 
southwestern Ohio and Eldora, Iowa. Wind gusting to 40 mph created 
blizzard conditions and northern Indiana's LaGrange County pulled 
its plows off the roads because snow was drifting 5 to 8 feet deep. 
At least a dozen deaths throughout the region were blamed on the 
storm. 

</P>
<P>
	Bus Crashes on N.J. Highway  
</P>
<P>
	DOVER, N.J. (AP) -- For the fourth time since Dec. 24, a  
casino-bound bus has been involved in a crash on a New Jersey 
highway. No one on the bus was injured in Saturday's multi-vehicle 
accident on the Garden State Parkway, and police said the bus 
continued on its trip to Atlantic City. A 13-year-old boy riding in 
another vehicle was in critical condition after icy conditions 
caused the pileup. He was taken by ambulance to Jersey Shore 
Medical Center. Ice storms struck the state Saturday night, causing 
a rash of accidents on New Jersey roads, including nearly a dozen 
on the Parkway alone. 

</P>
<P>
	Bin Laden Confronts Terrorist Role  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Suspected terrorist mastermind Osama bin Laden  
appears to admit he instigated the bombing of two U.S. embassies in 
Africa, Time magazine reports. The interview, conducted at bin 
Laden's secret Afghanistan encampment on Dec. 22, seems the closest 
the exiled Saudi billionaire has come to admitting a role in the 
deadly attacks. ``Our job is to instigate, and by the grace of God, 
we did that, and certain people responded to this instigation,'' 
bin Laden says in the Jan. 11 issue of Time magazine. 

</P>
<P>
	British Dead Return From Yemen  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The bodies of three British tourists killed during  
a shootout between Yemeni troops and a gang of kidnappers were 
returned to Britain late Saturday. Margaret Whitehouse, 52, Ruth 
Williamson, 34, and Peter Rowe, 60, along with 35-year-old 
Australian Andrew Thirsk died when Yemeni authorities launched a 
rescue operation Tuesday after the kidnapping of 16 Western 
tourists by Islamic extremists. 

</P>
<P>
	Angola Rebels Down UN Plane Again  
</P>
<P>
	LUANDA, Angola (AP) -- Rebel forces shot down a U.N.-chartered  
cargo plane Saturday, the second United Nations plane attacked in 
Angola's central highland war zone in eight days, U.N. officials 
said. The C-130 aircraft, with eight people aboard including one 
American, was hit by anti-aircraft fire 20 minutes after takeoff. 
Another U.N. plane, with 14 people aboard, crashed in the same area 
Dec. 26 while flying over an area of fighting between the 
government army and rebels. 

</P>
<P>
	Strong Aftershock Jolts SW China  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- A strong earthquake struck Sunday in a  
mountainous stretch of southwestern China where residents were 
recovering from two earlier quakes, a government seismologist said. 
No one was believed to have been killed or injured in the 
preliminary magnitude-5 quake, which hit Yunnan province's Ninglang 
region around 1 a.m., said the seismologist. The quake was an 
aftershock from twin quakes, one with a magnitude of 6.2, that 
jolted the region in November. The aftershock, which struck 1,200 
miles southwest of Beijing, was strong enough to cause moderate 
damage. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 7 Fla. 31, No. 18 Syracuse 10  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- So much for the notion that Florida is not as  
explosive as usual -- the seventh-ranked Gators rebounded from a 
loss in their regular-season finale with a dominating performance 
in a 31-10 rout of No. 18 Syracuse on Saturday night. Doug Johnson 
tossed two touchdown passes before breaking his left leg and Jesse 
Palmer threw for one score and ran for one, proving once again that 
Florida's offense flourishes regardless of who's at quarterback. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 10 UCLA Beats No. 6 Arizona  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Freshman Jerome Moiso scored 21 points and  
Baron Davis added 20 as UCLA's aggressive defense helped the 
10th-ranked Bruins beat No. 6 Arizona 82-75 Saturday night in the 
Pac-10 opener for both teams. The Bruins (9-2), who lost both 
meetings to Arizona last season, won their seventh straight in a 
game that wasn't close until the final two minutes. The Wildcats 
(8-1), the defending conference champions, faced a vocal, hostile 
crowd at Pauley Pavilion in only their second road game of the 
season. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
