<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 20:11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Jan. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole May Quit Red Cross  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a step her political supporters hope will  
lead to her running for the White House, Elizabeth Dole is reported 
to be stepping aside as president of the American Red Cross. 
Newsweek magazine quotes one of Dole's close advisers as saying her 
decision is a ``first step'' toward a possible bid for the 
Republican nomination. Red Cross officials would not confirm the 
report but announced late today that Dole will make a ``major'' 
announcement tomorrow afternoon in Washington. Mrs. Dole's husband, 
former Sen. Bob Dole, was the GOP presidential nominee in 1996 and 
she has consistently scored high in public opinion polls as a 
potential candidate. 

</P>
<P>
	Storm in Midwest Kills 28  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- At least 28 deaths are being blamed on the  
snowstorm that hit the Midwest this weekend. The biggest Chicago 
storm in more than 30 years also delayed air travelers across the 
Midwest. About 22 inches of snow had piled up from Chicago across 
northern Indiana as the storm spread snow, ice, slush and rain from 
the Missouri Valley to the East Coast. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Backs Health Care Credit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is proposing a $1,000 tax  
credit for American families struggling to provide long-term care 
for elderly or disabled relatives. The tax credit is part of a 
five-year, $6.2 billion package that the president and first lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton will announce tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Censure Plan Builds Strength  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate plan that may lead to the censure of  
President Clinton is gaining momentum. Proposed by one Democrat and 
one Republican, the plan would give the House prosecutors and the 
White House each one day to present the senate with their cases. 
After asking questions, senators would vote on whether charges 
against the president, even if true, were grave enough to remove 
him from office. If a two-thirds majority isn't reached, the Senate 
could adjourn the trial with a simple majority, then move to a 
possible censure motion against the president. 

</P>
<P>
	Mars Probe To Arrive in Dec.  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA today launched a spacecraft  
headed for the fringes of the Martian south polar cap to search for 
frozen water. The Polar Lander is due to arrive at Mars in December 
when it's late spring and the sun never sets. No spacecraft has 
ever ventured so far south on Mars. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler Unveils New Cars  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG unveiled a trio of concept  
cars and trucks today that represent the automaker's efforts to 
find near-term alternatives to conventional gasoline power. The 
Dodge Power Wagon is an oversized pickup packed with a 7.2-liter, 
turbocharged diesel engine designed to run on a synthetic 
diesel-type fuel derived from natural gas. Also unveiled was the 
Chrysler Citadel, a sport sedan with a hybrid powertrain, which 
uses a V6 engine to drive the rear wheels and an electric motor to 
drive the front wheels. And the Dodge Charger R/T uses a 
supercharged, 325-horsepower V8 engine powered by compressed 
natural gas. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall; Euro Debuts  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks plunged at the open of the year's  
first trading session. The euro, meanwhile, made its trading debut 
with little fanfare. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 281.34 points, 
or 2.03 percent, to 13,560.83 points in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. The euro was quoted at $1.1755, up from $1.1735 earlier in 
the session in Sydney. The new common currency is expected to 
increase Europe's power in the global economy and eventually rival 
the U.S. dollar as the money of choice for traders and reserves. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Boxer Quarry, Fought Ali, Dies  
</P>
<P>
	TEMPLETON, Calif. (AP) -- Former boxer Jerry Quarry, a popular  
heavyweight who fought Muhammad Ali and Floyd Patterson, has died 
at 53. Among the highlights of Quarry's career were two fights 
against Patterson, the former heavyweight champion. Quarry earned 
his biggest payday, $338,000, by fighting Ali when Ali returned 
from his banishment in 1970. Quarry finished his pro career with a 
53-9-4 record. But by the age of 50, the pounding he had taken in 
the ring turned him into a confused, childlike man whose relatives 
had to take care of him. 

</P>
<P>
	Niners Top Pack; Face Falcons  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The San Francisco 49ers beat the Green Bay  
Packers 30-27 in the NFC wild-card game today. The victory ended 
San Francisco's run of five straight losses to the Packers, 
including the last three playoffs. The 49ers travel to Atlanta next 
Saturday, where they face the Falcons. Earlier, the Jacksonville 
Jaguars beat the New England Patriots 25-10. They play the Jets in 
New York next Sunday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JAKE ULICK  

</P>
</TEXT>
