<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vols' Holdsclaw Likes New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw isn't shy about her desire to  
play professional basketball in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love to play here,'' Holdsclaw said after No. 2 Tennessee  
defeated No. 15 Rutgers 68-54 before a record crowd of 15,735 for a 
women's college game at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Astoria, Queens, Holdsclaw is expected to be the top  
pick in the WNBA draft in April. The Tennessee All-American had a 
season-low eight points before 100 friends and family, but she 
wasn't concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a season-low five points, but the next night I might  
have 30,'' she said. ``I know what I can do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So does New York Liberty coach Richie Adubato. But New York has  
the sixth pick in the 12-team draft. The last-place Washington 
Mystics have the top pick. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd love to get Chamique,'' Adubato said. ``Obviously, she's  
the cream of the crop. She's a multitalented player. We'll just 
have to see what happens with the draft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the demise of the American Basketball League, Holdsclaw is  
sure to land in the WNBA rather than go overseas to play 
professional basketball. But the likely influx of such ABL stars as 
Theresa Edwards, Natalie Williams, Jennifer Azzi, Jennifer Rizzotti 
and Katie Smith may affect the upcoming draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, I'll be the No. 1 pick, but if I'm not, that's  
cool,'' Holdsclaw said. ``They can pick me No. 6 so I can come to 
New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, the WNBA does not allow regional draft picks. Any  
changes in the draft rules would be made by the WNBA Operating 
Committee, said league spokesman Mark Pray. 
</P>
<P>
	Adubato said the committee would address the influx of ABL  
players and other issues within the next two months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regardless, I think she'll be the No. 1 pick,'' said Tennessee  
coach Pat Summitt. ``I think she'll have a great impact (in the 
WNBA). At 6-foot-2, with the versatile game she plays, she will 
bring excitement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw leads the Lady Vols in scoring (21.9) and averages 8.7  
rebounds. She guided Tennessee to a 39-0 record and its third 
consecutive NCAA title last season. Holdsclaw led Christ the King 
to four consecutive state high school championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with teammate Kellie Jollie, Holdsclaw has a chance to  
become the first player, male or female, to win four consecutive 
NCAA championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw was raised by her grandmother in an Astoria housing  
project. She played pick-up games with St. John's star Ron Artest 
growing up. She likes the idea of playing pro ball before friends 
and family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't have to make a major adjustments, because I'm from  
here,'' Holdsclaw said. ``I know where everything is. I have a lot 
of friends if I need somebody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Summitt expects Holdsclaw to get her wish sometime soon.  
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully that will work out for her, if not the first year, I  
think eventually.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
