<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Health Clubs Change With Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For 1999, health clubs are driving members up  
the wall and out the door. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen for activity that blurs the line between exercise and  
adventure is leading clubs to set up climbing walls inside, and 
taking members outside for club-led climbing trips and other 
challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clubs are taking members on biking excursions, mountaineering  
excursions, triathlon excursions -- the movement toward adventure is 
interesting and exciting,'' said John McCarthy, executive director 
of IHRSA, a Boston-based association of health clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	The search for something more daring than standard weight  
training and aerobic dance also is feeding interest in 
high-intensity, military-style workouts -- ``boot camps and GI Jane 
classes,'' McCarthy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The association does not have numbers on clubs with such  
programs, but word from the field indicates they are growing. 
</P>
<P>
	``People seem to be more hyped on doing something different -- a  
bit more extreme,'' said Ivan Greene, a professional climber who 
runs the climbing wall and the outdoor climbing expeditions at New 
York City's Sports Center at Chelsea Piers. 
</P>
<P>
	The indoor wall is 150 feet long, reaches 65 feet at its peak,  
and includes sufficient grips and overhangs to prepare participants 
for the outdoors, Greene said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Indoor climbing gives them the ability to try climbing in a  
safe, fun environment,'' he said. ``And it takes the edge off -- no 
pun intended -- climbing in the outdoors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The club normally takes its expeditions to the Shawangunk  
Mountains cliffs about 90 minutes north of New York. The club has 
sent other trips to Mexico and France. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sports Center also offers kayak training in an indoor pool,  
with participants eventually kayaking the Hudson River and New York 
Harbor, touring the George Washington Bridge and the Statue of 
Liberty from the water. 
</P>
<P>
	Something similar is happening on the opposite coast. The Frog's  
athletic club in San Diego takes members on outdoor team-event 
expeditions, said Roger Bates, the club's chief executive officer. 
Members are divided into three to five person groups for climbing, 
mountain biking, ocean and river kayaking, orienteering and 
rappelling. 
</P>
<P>
	``We charge a lot of extra money for that, but participation is  
phenomenal,'' Bates said. ``We get 30 to 50 people sign up and it's 
overbooked.'' It's adventure with creature comforts, he said -- ``We 
set up the camp, cater it and lay out the equipment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The club also runs an extensive outdoor exercise program modeled  
partly on the Navy SEAL physical training regimen, Bates said. ``We 
run them through the surf, and they do pushups on the beach,'' he 
said. ``We build obstacles out there, and they have to hang on 
things and climb on ropes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People like exercising outside, and the club can set up a  
specific program so members ``don't have to think about what is in 
their workout,'' Bates said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all of 1999's exercise trends will have participants acting  
like Indiana Jones. But many are battle-based. A survey of 15 
program directors in the United States and Canada found boxing- and 
martial arts-based classes among the top trends. The club officials 
said funk/hip hop and high-impact aerobic dance were on the way 
down. The results were in a group exercise leaders' magazine 
published by IDEA, a San Diego-based association of health and 
fitness professionals. 
</P>
<P>
	And personal training is growing, said the American Council on  
Exercise, another fitness professionals' group based in San Diego. 
Personal trainers are expanding beyond the rich, to offer services 
to people with more moderate incomes, said council spokesman Mark 
Anders. 
</P>
<P>
	To do this, trainers are offering fewer visits spread over a  
specific period, such as six months, instead of a standard two 
visits a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
