<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fiesta Bowl Opponents Pray Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Rev. Dan Yeary surveyed his congregation,  
swollen by about a hundred large young men and out-of-towners 
dressed in orange, and made an apology. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our choir could not learn Rocky Top in time for this,'' Yeary  
said, referring to the song that accompanies every Tennessee score. 
</P>
<P>
	On the eve of their battle for the national championship,  
Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer and Florida State coach Bobby Bowden 
joined in prayer Sunday at North Phoenix Baptist Church. Each coach 
gave personal testimony about his faith. 
</P>
<P>
	The entire Tennessee team also attended, surrounded by fans  
whose rental cars were festooned with orange flags and pompoms. 
Balloons -- orange and white for Tennessee, garnet and gold for the 
Seminoles -- were attached to some pews. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden and Fulmer sat across from each other in neighboring  
pews. Tennessee and Florida State fans sat side by side. Though the 
coaches were non-partisan in their testimony, Fulmer couldn't 
resist wearing a gaudy orange tie. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the day before a national championship, with all the stress  
and all the pressure, the leaders of these two teams have chosen to 
be in the Lord's house,'' Yeary said to the applause of his 
congregation. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee kicker Jeff Hall, a member of the Fellowship of  
Christian Athletes on campus, took the stage to tell Yeary about 
his devout upbringing and how he has changed his priorities in 
recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	While in high school and during his freshman year at Tennessee,  
Hall said, he put his faith ``on an even keel with football and 
social life.'' Now, he said, he understands the proper order. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to praise God so I could play football,'' he said,  
``and now I want to play football so I can praise the Lord.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yeary then let Hall in on a little secret. The reverend said his  
son also is a kicker, and Yeary said that has led him to root for 
all kickers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pull for me tomorrow, then,'' Hall said, laughing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
