<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Eyes Long-Term Care Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is proposing an  
unprecedented $1,000 tax credit, at a cost of billions, to 
compensate 2 million American families struggling to provide 
long-term care for elderly or disabled relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax credit, meant to compensate caregivers for a wide range  
of activities that tending to others requires, is part of a 
five-year, $6.2 billion package that the president and first lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton will announce Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	None of it becomes reality without Congress, which last year  
rejected the president's attempt at HMO reform through a ``Patients 
Bill of Rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to a draft proposal obtained by The Associated Press  
over the weekend, Clinton's four-part initiative also proposes that 
the government offer federal workers and retirees private long-term 
care insurance, in the hope that other employers would do the same. 
The White House estimates that 300,000 government employees would 
participate in a model program. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton will ask Congress for $625 million in grants, over a  
five-year period, to state and local ``agencies on aging,'' created 
by the 1965 Older Americans Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would be used to set up information and referral  
programs and to provide direct services to millions of daughters 
and sons coping with elderly parents at home. Services would 
include the same kinds meant to be compensated for by the proposed 
new tax credit: counseling and training for extraordinary care 
needs, such as feeding tubes; adult day care for dependents of 
working caregivers; and respite care, to fill in when a caregiver 
goes on vacation or just needs a break. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistance would be equally available to parents of disabled or  
chronically ill children and anybody else providing family care to 
a person, of whatever age, with three or more conditions that limit 
their ability to live as others do. 
</P>
<P>
	Another component of Clinton's plan would, at a cost of $10  
million, launch an information campaign to ensure that all 39 
million Medicare beneficiaries realize they are not covered for 
most long-term care. Documentation would advise them what to look 
for in supplementary private insurance and that they might be 
eligible for Medicaid long-term care benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Ari Fleischer, spokesman for House Ways and Means Committee  
Chairman Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, said the proposals had ``a lot 
of potential'' and would have a good chance of congressional 
approval if they are not accompanied by tax hikes. He said the 
ideas were part of House GOP ``Contract with America'' bills passed 
by the House in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, whose 90-year-old father died last month  
in Tennessee after a long infirmity, will speak for the initiative 
and its certain appeal to aging baby boomers in a series of forums 
around the nation. The administration will need to persuade a 
Republican-controlled Congress, with its own ideas for tax cuts and 
changes in the health-care system, to approve the long-term care 
programs and the money to pay for them. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House insists it can be done without touching the  
federal budget surplus, which Clinton has pledged to reserve for 
shoring up Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	A White House official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
the five-year, $5.5 billion cost of the tax credit would be borne 
by that standby of Washington policy-makers in search of an easy 
cost offset: tightening ``corporate welfare'' by closing loopholes 
in the tax code. 
</P>
<P>
	The other three prongs are meant to be worked into the fiscal  
2000 budget within agreed spending limits, the official said. ``The 
president has to make choices about his priorities, and this is one 
of them. It will not come out of the surplus,'' the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the director of Clinton's Office of Management and  
Budget said the tax credits will not overburden spending limits in 
the budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``This year's budget will be consistent with last year's,'' said  
OMB's Jack Lew. Speaking on CNN's ``Late Edition,'' Lew said all 
tax cuts would be accounted for when the overall plan is completed 
in several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	According to White House estimates, the $1,000 tax credit, which  
phases out for upper-income couples at $110,000 and at $75,000 for 
unmarried taxpayers, will be available to about 2 million 
Americans. The grants are expected to go to some 250,000 families 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 5 million Americans need long-term care due to chronic  
or serious illness, disability or simple old age. The number is 
growing as the baby boom generation nears retirement. By 2030, the 
number of Americans age 85 and older will jump from the current 4 
million to 8.4 million, and almost half of whom need assistance 
with daily activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Health policy experts have long advocated government help for  
stressed-out family caregivers as a way of avoiding expensive 
nursing homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 13:05:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Infertile Couples Want Grade A Eggs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Some infertile couples want strictly  
Grade A eggs. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the nation's biggest fertility registries has been  
focusing more advertising on newspapers at Ivy League schools as 
couples increasingly seek out eggs they hope will grow into brainy 
kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many parents are willing to be more flexible on the health  
history than on academic achievements and signs of intelligence,'' 
said Teri B. Royal, director of the Los Angeles-based OPTIONS 
National Fertility Registry. While prospective parents choose 
donors based on physical characteristics, intelligence ``is 
probably the most sought-after attribute,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of couples requesting advertising at the Ivies has  
nearly doubled each year since OPTIONS opened for business in 1992, 
Royal said. She said she believes the public has grown more open to 
alternative methods of reproduction, including people who went to 
the Ivies, once bastions of tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	Other fertility agencies said they don't tally the number of  
people who want Ivy League donors and that their official policy is 
to discourage that sort of targeted search. However, advertising 
managers at Ivy League newspapers say such ads are on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to land an Ivy League donor is neither easy nor cheap.  
OPTIONS represents one alumna who spent more than $15,000 in 
advertising at the top schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The response rate to the OPTIONS advertisements is about 75  
percent lower among Ivy coeds than among young women at other 
schools, Royal said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the students that go to the Ivy League schools come  
from families that have at least a minimum of wealth and generally 
are not looking through want ads or employment ads to supplement 
their income,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	If they are interested, however, young women from the Ivy League  
or elsewhere can make anywhere from $3,500 to $5,000 for 
contributing ova. Other advertisements have offered more, some as 
much as $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	A New Jersey couple who went through OPTIONS to get a donor say  
parents should only go so far to try and product a genetically 
perfect child. 
</P>
<P>
	Janet Lasley and Marc Brahaney, himself a Princeton graduate,  
describe their 1 1/2-year-old son, Charlie, as ``brilliant,'' -- 
despite that the egg donor wasn't an Ivy Leaguer. They did note, 
however, that she got a 1,270 on her SATs, earned A's in college 
and has an IQ of 146. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a much more of an emotional connection than for me to  
genetically engineer this thing,'' said Ms. Lasley, 45. ``There is 
that temptation ... but once you get this child, it doesn't matter. 
You just love them, no matter what.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An Ivy League donor doesn't guarantee an Ivy League kid, Royal  
notes. She advertises in other places, as does the Columbia 
University Presbyterian Medical Center. In an effort to serve 
clients who request it, however, the hospital began running 
advertisements in the Columbia Daily Spectator last semester when 
the paper changed its policy and began accepting such ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Richard Scott, director of the Institute for Reproductive  
Medicine &AMP; Science at Saint Barnabas Medical Center in Livingston, 
N.J., said that no matter how intelligent the donor, medical 
science cannot pinpoint the origins of genius, or reproduce them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an age-old debate, nature versus nurture,'' said Scott.  
``We've certainly had an occasional recipient who's very concerned 
with educational levels, but health is usually the overriding 
concern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some who carry the supposedly elite eggs find the topic somewhat  
amusing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the ads are looking for me,'' joked Karen Abrecht, 20,  
a tall Yale junior with brown hair, blue eyes and love of history. 
``They must think that for some reason the genes I would have to 
offer would somehow be better, even though it's never been proven 
scientifically.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990103.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 23:42:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Memories of Ice Storm Still Fresh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) -- The sounds were frightening, alarmingly  
like the noises of battle. Trees and limbs broke with loud cracks, 
then fell with thundering crashes like mortar rounds. Ice on the 
branches shattered as it hit the crust of frozen snow, rattling 
like machine-gun fire. 
</P>
<P>
	All day, all night.  
</P>
<P>
	A year later, reminders linger of the ice storm that left  
hundreds of thousands without electricity: topless trees along the 
interstate, ragged limbs still dangling, prodigious stacks of 
firewood in yards. Newly purchased generators sit in garages and 
barns, ready for a repeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say they're never going to be caught short again,'' said  
Gil Steward, sales manager of a Lewiston business that sold 550 
generators in the aftermath of the two-day ice storm -- more than 
five times the number he normally sells in a year. 
</P>
<P>
	It all began with a seemingly harmless light rain the evening of  
Jan. 7, 1998. But the freezing rain soon formed an inches-thick 
veneer of ice that caused branches to sag, then snap under the 
weight. 
</P>
<P>
	Before it was over, 700,000 of the state's 1.2 million residents  
were in the dark. Some had no power for as long as two weeks. A 
federal disaster was declared and damage was estimated at $100 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the only consolation of the storm was that temperatures  
didn't drop to the brutally cold subzero range, as often happens in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were just lucky it didn't get real cold,'' said Clark  
Hatto, whose family survived without electricity for a period that 
he recalls lasted exactly ``seven days and seven hours.'' They kept 
the gas stove burning day and night. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastern Maine was among the hardest-hit areas, where nine miles  
of H-shaped wooden power-line supports broke like toothpicks under 
the enormous weight of the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	Central Maine Power, the state's largest electric utility,  
replaced more than 3,000 poles after the storm. The utility is 
still trying to recover $50 million of its $65 million storm cost 
from the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	Maine wasn't alone in the misery. About 70,000 homes and  
business were left in the dark in New Hampshire, and Canada was hit 
even harder. At least two dozen people died in Quebec and Ontario, 
where nearly 1 million customers were left without power. 
</P>
<P>
	In Maine, at least a dozen deaths were linked to the storm,  
including seven carbon monoxide poisonings from heaters and 
generators used in poorly ventilated areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Restoring power was the biggest challenge. Central Maine had to  
learn literally overnight how to organize and run a major 
construction effort in the middle of January. 
</P>
<P>
	The company brought in nearly 3,900 people from as far away as  
North Carolina who worked 18-hour shifts for 23 straight days, said 
President Sara Burns. To keep the troops fed, Central Maine 
provided as many as 1,500 lunches a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Work crews devoted much of the spring and summer to clearing  
felled branches and trimming trees, but outages of such magnitude 
could occur again, said Central Maine spokesman Mark Ishkanian. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we ever had an ice buildup like we did last year, no amount  
of tree trimming would prevent the kind of devastation that 
happened last January,'' he said. ``Aesthetically, it wouldn't be 
tolerated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those who lived through the ordeal remember acts of kindness  
that softened the harsh impacts. 
</P>
<P>
	People came out of dark houses to give line workers food and hot  
coffee; strangers picked up their tabs at diners and cafes. One 
woman organized 250 people to bake cookies for the utility workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't get over the way people treated us, especially in  
those terrible conditions,'' said line supervisor Richard 
Harrington, who was so impressed by Mainers' spirit that he became 
one. 
</P>
<P>
	When Harrington returned to Lavallette, N.J., after working two  
weeks in Maine, a half dozen letters of thanks were waiting for 
him.. 
</P>
<P>
	He persuaded his wife, Abby, to return with him for a huge  
lobster feed offered outside the State House in Augusta in July, 
where Gov. Angus King thanked the repair crews. 
</P>
<P>
	The Harringtons have been living in Maine for three months and  
are building a home in Rockport. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of hard to believe, but it's true,'' he said. ``It's  
all been a positive experience since.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
